Oarfoot: Any crustacean of the genus Remipes.
Orograph: A machine for use in making topographical maps.  It is operated by being pushed across country, and not only records distances, like the perambulator, but also elevations.
Omnipotent: Able in every respect and for every work; unlimited in ability; all-powerful; almighty; as, the Being that can create worlds must be omnipotent.
oxalacetate: a salt or ester of oxalacetic acid.
&Verbar;Oblongum: A prolate spheroid; a figure described by the revolution of an ellipse about its greater axis.  Cf. Oblatum, and see Ellipsoid of revolution, under Ellipsoid.
Omnipresent: Present in all places at the same time; ubiquitous; as, the omnipresent Jehovah.
Osteoplasty: An operation or process by which the total or partial loss of a bone is remedied.
Orthotropal: Having the axis of an ovule or seed straight from the hilum and chalaza to the orifice or the micropyle; atropous.
Operculum: The lid of a pitcherform leaf.
Ovarious: Consisting of eggs; as, ovarious food.
Oppositive: Capable of being put in opposition.
Ostentation: The act of ostentating or of making an ambitious display; unnecessary show; pretentious parade; -- usually in a detractive sense.
Ordalian: Of or pertaining to trial by ordeal.
Oke: A Turkish and Egyptian weight, equal to about 23/4 pounds.
\u0152nanthol: An oily substance (C6H15.CHO) obtained by the distillation of castor oil, recognized as the aldehyde of œnanthylic acid, and hence called also œnanthaldehyde.
Overtax: To tax or to task too heavily; as, a job that overtaxed his physical energies.
Overweigh: To exceed in weight; to overbalance; to weigh down.
Oxide: A binary compound of oxygen with an atom or radical, or a compound which is regarded as binary; as, iron oxide, ethyl oxide, nitrogen oxide, etc.
&Verbar;Ommatidium: One of the single eyes forming the compound eyes of crustaceans, insects, and other invertebrates; one of the eyes of an ommateum.
Outguard: A guard or small body of troops at a distance from the main body of an army, to watch for the approach of an enemy; hence, anything for defense placed at a distance from the thing to be defended.
Opisthoc\u0153lian: Concave behind; -- applied especially to vertebræ in which the anterior end of the centrum is convex and the posterior concave.
Ovist: A believer in ovism.  Same as Ovulist.
osteo-: A combining form of Gr. 'oste`on a bone.
Orthite: A variety of allanite occurring in slender prismatic crystals.
Ossific: Capable of producing bone; having the power to change cartilage or other tissue into bone.
Operand: The symbol, quantity, or thing upon which a mathematical operation is performed; -- called also faciend.
onside kick: A kickoff in which the kicking team attempts to kick the ball only so far as is legally required (beyond the 50-yard line), so as to have a better chance to recover the kicked ball itself; -- it is a risky type of play used only when the kicking team is losing and there is little time left to play.
Omniformity: The condition or quality of having every form.
orzo: Pasta shaped like pearls of barley; frequently prepared with lamb in Greek cuisine.
Occupation: The act or process of occupying or taking possession; actual possession and control; the state of being occupied; a holding or keeping; tenure; use; as, the occupation of lands by a tenant.
ornamental: Serving to ornament; characterized by ornament; beautifying; embellishing.
Outflank: To go beyond, or be superior to, on the flank; to pass around or turn the flank or flanks of.
Olfactory: An olfactory organ; also, the sense of smell; -- usually in the plural.
Overhip: To pass over by, or as by a hop; to skip over; hence, to overpass.
Ovariotomy: The operation of removing one or both of the ovaries; oöphorectomy.
Outbid: To exceed or surpass in bidding; to bid a higher price.
Osnaburg: A species of coarse linen, originally made in Osnaburg, Germany.
Ovicapsule: The outer layer of a Graafian follicle.
Oratorian: See Fathers of the Oratory, under Oratory.
&Verbar;Ouakari: Any South American monkey of the genus Brachyurus, especially Brachyurus ouakari.
Otherness: The quality or state of being other or different; alterity; oppositeness.
Orphanage: The state of being an orphan; orphanhood; orphans, collectively.
Oscinian: Any one of numerous species of dipterous flies of the family Oscinidæ.
octandrian: Of or pertaining to the Octandria; having eight distinct stamens.
Orderly: A noncommissioned officer or soldier who attends a superior officer to carry his orders, or to render other service.
Oxybenzoic: Hydroxybenzoic; pertaining to, or designating, any one of several hydroxyl derivatives of benzonic acid, of which the commonest is salicylic acid.
Organizability: Quality of being organizable; capability of being organized.
Octopus: A genus of eight-armed cephalopods, including numerous species, some of them of large size.  See Devilfish.
Obvention: The act of happening incidentally; that which happens casually; an incidental advantage; an occasional offering.
Opuntiales: An order of plants coextensive with the family Cactaceae, comprising the cactuses.
Opportunist: One who advocates or practices opportunism.
&Verbar;Ostrea: A genus of bivalve Mollusca which includes the true oysters.
Opportunism: The art or practice of taking advantage of opportunities or circumstances, or of seeking immediate advantage with little regard for ultimate consequences.
Oppugnancy: The act of oppugning; opposition; resistance.
Ostiary: The mouth of a river; an estuary.
\u0152struation: The state of being under œstrual influence, or of having sexual desire.
Ornithoscopy: Observation of birds and their habits.
Overhandle: To handle, or use, too much; to mention too often.
Obstetricious: Serving to assist childbirth; obstetric; hence, facilitating any bringing forth or deliverance.
off-site: Taking place or located away from the specified site; as, an off-site waste treatment operation.  Opposite to on-site.
Offshore: From the shore; as, an offshore wind; an offshore signal.
Overarch: To make or place an arch over; to hang over like an arch.
Oquassa: A small, handsome trout (Salvelinus oquassa), found in some of the lakes in Maine; -- called also blueback trout.
Onagra: Same as Oenothera, a genus of plants consisting of the evening primrose.
&Verbar;Odonata: The division of insects that includes the dragon flies.
Outstay: To stay beyond or longer than.
Omphalopsychite: A name of the Hesychasts, from their habit of gazing upon the navel.
Outsit: To remain sitting, or in session, longer than, or beyond the time of; to outstay.
&Verbar;Oblati: Children dedicated in their early years to the monastic state.
Outspread: To spread out; to expand; -- usually as a past part. or adj.
Orthodoxy: Soundness of faith; a belief in the doctrines taught in the Scriptures, or in some established standard of faith; -- opposed to heterodoxy or to heresy.
Outing: The act of going out; an airing; an excursion; as, a summer outing.
Ovarian: Of or pertaining to an ovary.
Ostiole: The exterior opening of a stomate. See Stomate.
Occasion: To give occasion to; to cause; to produce; to induce; as, to occasion anxiety.
Olefiant: Forming or producing an oil; specifically, designating a colorless gaseous hydrocarbon called ethylene (olefiant gas).
Overprompt: Too prompt; too ready or eager; precipitate.
Ortive: Of or relating to the time or act of rising; eastern; as, the ortive amplitude of a planet.
over-embellished: marked by elaborate rhetoric and many figures of speech.
Overtime: Time beyond, or in excess of, a limit; esp., extra working time.
Overlander: One who travels over lands or countries; one who travels overland.
Orion: A large and bright constellation on the equator, between the stars Aldebaran and Sirius.  It contains a remarkable nebula visible to the naked eye.
Outrider: A summoner whose office is to cite men before the sheriff.
Outcrier: One who cries out or proclaims; a herald or crier.
offenceless: incapable of offending or attacking; harmless.
Otherguise: Of another kind or sort; in another way.
Omnipresence: Presence in every place at the same time; unbounded or universal presence; ubiquity.
&Verbar;Odontornithes: A group of Mesozoic birds having the jaws armed with teeth, as in most other vertebrates. They have been divided into three orders: Odontolcæ, Odontotormæ, and Saururæ.
organized: same as arranged; as, an organized tour.
&Verbar;Osteoma: A tumor composed mainly of bone; a tumor of a bone.
&Verbar;Oca: A Peruvian name for certain species of Oxalis (Oxalis crenata, and Oxalis tuberosa) which bear edible tubers.
Octoyl: A hypothetical radical (C7H15.CO.), regarded as the essential residue of octoic acid.
Oberon: The king of the fairies, and husband of Titania or Queen Mab.
Overgrace: To grace or honor exceedingly or beyond desert.
Octostyle: Having eight columns in the front; -- said of a temple or portico.  The Parthenon is octostyle, but most large Greek temples are hexastyle. See Hexastyle.
Overlie: To lie over or upon; specifically, to suffocate by lying upon; as, to overlie an infant.
Overshade: To cover with shade; to render dark or gloomy; to overshadow.
Oxpecker: An African bird of the genus Buphaga; the beefeater.
Obsecratory: Expressing, or used in, entreaty; supplicatory.
Olympic games: A modified revival of the ancient Olympian games, consisting of international athletic games, races, etc., now held once in four years, the first having been at Athens in 1896.
Ordinability: Capability of being ordained or appointed.
Octennial: Happening every eighth year; also, lasting a period of eight years.
outfight: to exceed in fighting; fight more competently; as, He outfought his challengers; the boxer outfought his opponent for eight rounds but lost the bout in the ninth on a knockout.
Ocean: Of or pertaining to the main or great sea; as, the ocean waves; an ocean stream.
Octillion: According to the French method of numeration (which method is followed also in the United States) the number expressed by a unit with twenty-seven ciphers annexed.  According to the English method, the number expressed by a unit with forty-eight ciphers annexed. See Numeration.
Omo-: A combining form used in anatomy to indicate connection with, or relation to, the shoulder or the scapula.
Outgeneral: To exceed in generalship; to gain advantage over by superior military skill or executive ability; to outmaneuver.
Oriolidae: A natural family of Old World orioles.
Outbreathe: To issue, as breath; to be breathed out; to exhale.
Overmarch: To march too far, or too much; to exhaust by marching.
Odoriferous: Bearing or yielding an odor; perfumed; usually, sweet of scent; fragrant; as, odoriferous spices, particles, fumes, breezes.
Oracular: Of or pertaining to an oracle; uttering oracles; forecasting the future; as, an oracular tongue.
Outlast: To exceed in duration; to survive; to endure longer than.
Osseous: Composed of bone; resembling bone; capable of forming bone; bony; ossific.
Oxybromic: Pertaining to, or designating, certain compounds of oxygen and bromine.
Overproduction: Excessive production; supply beyond the demand.
Oreopteris: A genus  of ferns having species, formerly included in genus Dryopteris or Thelypteris.
obligational: relating or constituting or qualified to create a legal or financial obligation; as, obligational authority.
Odontograph: An instrument for marking or laying off the outlines of teeth of gear wheels.
Ordinary: An officer who has original jurisdiction in his own right, and not by deputation.
Ostensibly: In an ostensible manner; avowedly; professedly; apparently.
Orthometric: Having the axes at right angles to one another; -- said of crystals or crystalline forms.
obiter dictum: An incidental and collateral opinion uttered by a judge. See Dictum, n., 2 (a).
Observe: To take notice; to give attention to what one sees or hears; to attend.
&Verbar;Orthopn\u0153a: Specifically, a morbid condition in which respiration can be performed only in an erect posture; by extension, any difficulty of breathing.
Originative: Having power, or tending, to originate, or bring into existence; originating.
Offerer: One who offers; esp., one who offers something to God in worship.
On-looker: A person who observes an event; a looker-on; a spectator.
Oyster: Any marine bivalve mollusk of the genus Ostrea. They are usually found adhering to rocks or other fixed objects in shallow water along the seacoasts, or in brackish water in the mouth of rivers. The common European oyster (Ostrea edulis), and the American oyster (Ostrea Virginiana), are the most important species.
Oxidulated: Existing in the state of a protoxide; -- said of an oxide.
Observatory: A place or building for making observations on the heavenly bodies.
Organist: One who plays on the organ.
Overruler: One who, or that which, controls, governs, or determines.
O\u00f6sporic: Of or pertaining to an oöspore.
Orthotomous: Having two cleavages at right angles with one another.
Ordeal: Of or pertaining to trial by ordeal.
Ostreaceous: Of or pertaining to an oyster, or to a shell; shelly.
Otologist: One skilled in otology; an aurist.
Orangeman: One of a secret society, organized in the north of Ireland in 1795, the professed objects of which are the defense of the reigning sovereign of Great Britain, the support of the Protestant religion, the maintenance of the laws of the kingdom, etc.; -- so called in honor of William, Prince of Orange, who became William III. of England.
Oxonic: Pertaining to, or designating, a complex nitrogenous acid (C4H5N3O4) not known in the free state, but obtained, in combination with its salts, by a slow oxidation of uric acid, to which it is related.
&Verbar;Odontolcae: An extinct order of ostrichlike aquatic birds having teeth, which are set in a groove in the jaw.  It includes Hesperornis, and allied genera. See Hesperornis.
Owlish: Resembling, or characteristic of, an owl.
Orthographic: Of or pertaining to orthography, or right spelling; also, correct in spelling; as, orthographical rules; the letter was orthographic.
Osteodentine: A hard substance, somewhat like bone, which is sometimes deposited within the pulp cavity of teeth.
Oleosity: The state or quality of being oily or fat; fatness.
Overawe: To awe exceedingly; to intimidate or subjugate or restrain by awe or great fear.
Objector: One who objects; one who offers objections to a proposition or measure.
Omnifarious: Of all varieties, forms, or kinds.
Operameter: An instrument or machine for measuring work done, especially for ascertaining the number of rotations made by a machine or wheel in manufacturing cloth; a counter.
Outlaugh: To surpass or outdo in laughing.
Oneirocritic: Of or pertaining to the interpretation of dreams.
Ossify: To become bone; to change from a soft tissue to a hard bony tissue.
&Verbar;Orbulina: A genus of minute living Foraminifera having a globular shell.
overutilize: To exploit to the point of diminishing returns; to use excessively.
Oafish: Like an oaf; simple or clumsy.
Overoffice: To domineer over by virtue of office.
oilcloth: Cloth rendered waterproof by treatment with oil or paint, and used for marking garments, covering tables, shelves, floors, etc.
Oxalite: A yellow mineral consisting of oxalate of iron.
Ornamentation: The act or art of ornamenting, or the state of being ornamented.
Overpart: To give too important or difficult a part to.
&Verbar;O\u00efdium: A genus of minute fungi which form a floccose mass of filaments on decaying fruit, etc.  Many forms once referred to this genus are now believed to be temporary conditions of fungi of other genera, among them the vine mildew (Oïdium Tuckeri), which has caused much injury to grapes.
Octavalent: Having a valence of eight; capable of being combined with, exchanged for, or compared with, eight atoms of hydrogen; -- said of certain atoms or radicals.
out-of-sight: very good; same as groovy, sense 1.
Overname: To name over or in a series; to recount.
Ouananiche: A small landlocked variety of the Atlantic salmon (Salmo salar ounaniche) of Lake St. John, Canada, and neighboring waters, noted for its vigor and activity, and habit of leaping from the water when hooked.
organized crime: Groups of persons organized for illegal purposes, such as bootlegging, conducting illegal gambling, loansharking, extortion, etc.; -- a general term encompassing most forms of criminal groups, but especially those that are consolidated into “families” more or less recognizing each other's different regions of operation; sometimes considered synonymous with the mafia or the syndicate.
Originally: In the original time, or in an original manner; primarily; from the beginning or origin; not by derivation, or imitation.
Obsolescent: Going out of use; becoming obsolete; passing into desuetude.
Omened: Attended by, or containing, an omen or omens; as, happy-omened day; an ill-omened venture.
Ozonometer: An instrument for ascertaining the amount of ozone in the atmosphere, or in any gaseous mixture.
Oarsweed: Any large seaweed of the genus Laminaria; tangle; kelp.  See Kelp.
Obstetrication: The act of assisting as a midwife; delivery.
Omission: The act of omitting; neglect or failure to do something required by propriety or duty.
&Verbar;Orthoptera: An order of mandibulate insects including grasshoppers, locusts, cockroaches, mantids, crickets, katydids, etc.  See Illust. under Insect.
one-up: Ahead of a friend or competitor in some competitive activity.
&Verbar;Ovum: A more or less spherical and transparent cell, which by a process of multiplication and growth develops into a mass of cells, constituting a new individual like the parent; an egg, spore, germ, or germ cell. See Illust. of Mycropyle.
Officinal: Used in a shop, or belonging to it.
ostracoid: Of or pertaining to the Ostracoidea (now Ostracoda).
Overcarking: Too anxious; too full of care.
&Verbar;Ostracoda: An order of Entomostraca possessing shrimplike bodies enclosed in hard bivalve shells; called also seed shrimp and mussel shrimp.  They were formerly referred to as Ostracoidea.  They are of small size, and swim freely about;  many are less than 1 mm in length.  Microfossils of certain extinct orders have been found extending back to the Cambrian age.
Otoscope: An instrument for examining the condition of the ear.
Obituary: Of or pertaining to the death of a person or persons; as, an obituary notice; obituary poetry.
osmotic: Pertaining to, or having the property of, osmosis; as, osmotic force.
Orangeade: A drink made of orange juice and water, corresponding to lemonade; orange sherbet.
Overweary: To weary too much; to tire out.
onomancy: Divination by the letters of a name; nomancy.
Orichalceous: Pertaining to, or resembling, orichalch; having a color or luster like that of brass.
Outrage: To be guilty of an outrage; to act outrageously.
Overhaul: A strict examination with a view to correction or repairs.
Ophiologist: One versed in the natural history of serpents.
Oblongatal: Of or pertaining to the medulla oblongata; medullar.
Otoscopy: The examination of the ear; the art of using the otoscope.
ortho\u00ebpist: One who is skilled in orthoëpy.
overlearned: Learned by repetitive practice or memorization, beyond the point where it can be immediately recalled.
Outground: Ground situated at a distance from the house; outlying land.
Overanxious: Anxious in an excessive or needless degree.
Oligarchy: A form of government in which the supreme power is placed in the hands of a few persons; also, those who form the ruling few.
Ostic: Pertaining to, or applied to, the language of the Tuscaroras, Iroquois, Wyandots, Winnebagoes, and a part of the Sioux Indians.
Objectist: One who adheres to, or is skilled in, the objective philosophy.
Oxamethane: Ethyl oxamate, obtained as a white scaly crystalline powder.
Oleandra: A genus of tropical epiphytic or terrestrial ferns; also classed as the family Polypodiaceae.
Oxamide: A white crystalline neutral substance (C2O2(NH2)2) obtained by treating ethyl oxalate with ammonia. It is the acid amide of oxalic acid.  Formerly called also oxalamide.
Outclimb: To climb beyond; to surpass in climbing.
orgasm: Eager or immoderate excitement or action; the state of turgescence of any organ; erethism.
oil heater: A heating or cooking device that burns oil (such as kerosine) as a fuel.
Ovalbumin: The albumin from white of eggs; egg albumin; -- in distinction from serum albumin. See Albumin.
Ousel: One of several species of European thrushes, especially the blackbird (Merula merula, or Turdus merula), and the mountain or ring ousel (Turdus torquatus).
Out-of-door: Being out of the house; being, or done, in the open air; suited for the open air; outdoor; as, out-of-door exercise. See Out of door, under Out, adv.
Overlord: One who is lord over another or others; a superior lord; a master.
Offensive: The state or posture of one who offends or makes attack; aggressive attitude; the act of the attacking party; -- opposed to defensive.
Oilstone: A variety of hone slate, or whetstone, used for whetting tools when lubricated with oil.
Ossianic: Of or pertaining to, or characteristic of, Ossian, a legendary Erse or Celtic bard.
Odeon: A kind of theater in ancient Greece, smaller than the dramatic theater and roofed over, in which poets and musicians submitted their works to the approval of the public, and contended for prizes; -- hence, in modern usage, the name of a hall for musical or dramatic performances.
Otocranial: Of or pertaining to the otocrane.
Omen: To divine or to foreshow by signs or portents; to have omens or premonitions regarding; to predict; to augur; as, to omen ill of an enterprise.
Optometry: Measurement of the range of vision, esp. by means of the optometer.
owner-driver: a motorist who owns the vehicle that he/she drives.
Outargue: To surpass or conquer in argument.
Oilnut: The buffalo nut. See Buffalo nut, under Buffalo.
Osages: A tribe of southern Sioux Indians, now living in the Indian Territory.
O\u00f6type: The part of the oviduct of certain trematode worms in which the ova are completed and furnished with a shell.
overachiever: a student who attains higher standards than expected based on the IQ score.
Occultness: State or quality of being occult.
O\u00f6ticoid: A half oviparous, or an oviparous, mammal; a marsupial or monotreme.
Obtunder: That which obtunds or blunts; especially, that which blunts sensibility.
Ordinal: A word or number denoting order or succession.
Orbation: The state of being orbate, or deprived of parents or children; privation, in general; bereavement.
oil-fired: Using oil as a fuel; as, an oil-fired furnace.
&Verbar;Orohippus: A genus of American Eocene mammals allied to the horse, but having four toes in front and three behind.
Omittance: The act of omitting, or the state of being omitted; forbearance; neglect.
Optics: That branch of physical science which treats of the nature and properties of light, the laws of its modification by opaque and transparent bodies, and the phenomena of vision.
Octonary: Of or pertaining to the number eight.
Outness: The state of being out or beyond; separateness.
Osteogenetic: Connected with osteogenesis, or the formation of bone; producing bone; as, osteogenetic tissue; the osteogenetic layer of the periosteum.
Obsolete: To become obsolete; to go out of use.
Ordainable: Capable of being ordained; worthy to be ordained or appointed.
Orthodiagonal: The diagonal or lateral axis in a monoclinic crystal which is at right angles with the vertical axis.
Outbrag: To surpass in bragging; hence, to make appear inferior.
Obtuse: Not pointed or acute; blunt; -- applied esp. to angles greater than a right angle, or containing more than ninety degrees.
ousting: the act of ejecting someone or forcing them out; ouster.
Obedience: The act of obeying, or the state of being obedient; compliance with that which is required by authority; subjection to rightful restraint or control.
Overspin: To spin out to too great length; to protract unduly.
oystercatcher: Any one of several species of wading birds of the genus Hæmatopus having stout legs and bill and mostly black-and-white plumage, which frequent seashores and feed upon oysters and other shellfish.  The European species (Hæmatopus ostralegus), the common American species (Hæmatopus palliatus), and the California, or black, oyster catcher (Hæmatopus Bachmani) are the best known.
-oid: A suffix or combining form meaning like, resembling, in the form of; as in anthropoid, asteroid, spheroid.
Ossean: A fish having a bony skeleton; a teleost.
Overshadower: One that throws a shade, or shadow, over anything.
Osmazome: A substance formerly supposed to give to soup and broth their characteristic odor, and probably consisting of one or several of the class of nitrogenous substances which are called extractives.
Octavo: Having eight leaves to a sheet; as, an octavo form, book, leaf, size, etc.
Obtenebration: The act of darkening; the state of being darkened; darkness.
off-the-rack: Intended to be worn without alterations; ready-to-wear; -- of clothing.  Contrasted with made-to-order, custom-made.
Overgloom: To spread gloom over; to make gloomy; to overshadow.
Overliness: The quality or state of being overly; carelessness.
Ophioglossales: An order coextensive with the family Ophioglossaceae.
Opiate: To subject to the influence of an opiate; to put to sleep.
Overpay: To pay too much to; to reward too highly.
Overween: To think too highly or arrogantly; to regard one's own thinking or conclusions too highly; hence, to be egotistic, arrogant, or rash, in opinion; to think conceitedly; to presume.
Orpiment: Arsenic sesquisulphide, produced artificially as an amorphous lemon-yellow powder, and occurring naturally as a yellow crystalline mineral; -- formerly called auripigment.  It is used in king's yellow, in white Indian fire, and in certain technical processes, as indigo printing.
outrange: to have a greater range than; -- of guns or missiles.
Observator: One who observes or takes notice.
Overproof: Containing more alcohol than proof spirit; stronger than proof spirit; that is, containing more than 49.3 per cent by weight of alcohol.
Oven: A place arched over with brick or stonework, and used for baking, heating, or drying; hence, any structure, whether fixed or portable, which may be heated for baking, drying, etc.; esp., now, a chamber in a stove, used for baking or roasting.
Octo-: A combining form meaning eight; as in octodecimal, octolocular.
Obolo: A copper coin, used in the Ionian Islands, about one cent in value.
Oblong-ovate: Between oblong and ovate, but inclined to the latter.
&Verbar;Opuntia: A genus of cactaceous plants; the prickly pear, or Indian fig.
Oviferous: Egg-bearing; -- applied particularly to certain receptacles, as in Crustacea, that retain the eggs after they have been excluded from the formative organs, until they are hatched.
\u0152nanthylic: Pertaining to, derived from, or containing, œnanthyl; specifically, designating an acid formerly supposed to be identical with the acid in œnanthic ether, but now known to be identical with heptanoic acid.
Obtusion: The act or process of making obtuse or blunt.
Oxaluric: Pertaining to, or designating, a complex nitrogenous acid related to the ureids, and obtained from parabanic acid as a white silky crystalline substance.
observed: perceived with the eyes and sometimes with other senses; as, no explanation for the observed phenomena.
Olympian: Pertaining to, characteristic of, or fitting for one of the gods on Olympus; grand, majestic, or aloof.
Orthocenter: That point in which the three perpendiculars let fall from the angles of a triangle upon the opposite sides, or the sides produced, mutually intersect.
Olympiad: A period of four years, by which the ancient Greeks reckoned time, being the interval from one celebration of the Olympic games to another, beginning with the victory of Corœbus in the foot race, which took place in the year 776 b. c.; as, the era of the olympiads.
optimum: The most favorable condition, greatest degree, or largest amount possible under given circumstances.
Overstrain: To stretch or strain too much; as, to overstrain one's nerves.
over-embellish: To embellish excessively; to render too ornate or complicated.
Outlier: One who does not live where his office, or business, or estate, is.
obsecrate: To beseech; to supplicate; to implore.
occupational: Of or pertaining to an occupation{3} or occupations{3}; caused by or incidental to an occupation{3}; as, occupational hazard; occupational illness.
Opprobrium: A state of disgrace; infamy; reproach mingled with contempt; odium{3}.
Orangeroot: An American ranunculaceous plant (Hidrastis Canadensis), having a yellow tuberous root; -- also called yellowroot, golden seal, etc.
Oniscus: The type genus of the Oniscidae, consisting of woodlice that cannot roll into a ball.
Omnibus: A long vehicle, having seats for many people; a bus.
Osiris: One of the principal divinities of Egypt, the brother and husband of Isis.  He was figured as a mummy wearing the royal cap of Upper Egypt, and was symbolized by the sacred bull, called Apis.  Cf. Serapis.
Oblivion: The act of forgetting, or the state of being forgotten; cessation of remembrance; forgetfulness.
orthodontist: a dentist specializing in the prevention or correction of irregularities of the teeth; one specializing in orthodontics.
Oversorrow: To grieve or afflict to excess.
owner-occupier: a occupant who owns the home that he/she lives in.
oceanographer: A scientist who studies physical and biological aspects of the seas.
Ogreish: Resembling an ogre; having the character or appearance of an ogre; suitable for an ogre.
Ozonometry: The measurement or determination of the quantity of ozone.
Onomasticon: A collection of names and terms; a dictionary; specif., a collection of Greek names, with explanatory notes, made by Julius Pollux about a. d. 180.
Outpray: To exceed or excel in prayer.
open-collared: not buttoned at the neck; -- of a shirt; as, dressed casually in shorts and an open-collared shirt.
owner-occupied: lived in by the owner; -- of dwellings.

Overdye: To dye with excess of color; to put one color over (another).

Oscule: One of the excurrent apertures of sponges.

Organizable: Capable of being organized; esp. (Biol.), capable of being formed into living tissue; as, organizable matter.
Obstructionism: The act or the policy of obstructing progress.
Oculary: Of or pertaining to the eye; ocular; optic; as, oculary medicines.

Orthopterous: Of or pertaining to the Orthoptera.
Obliteration: The act of obliterating, or the state of being obliterated; extinction.
Ontology: That department of the science of metaphysics which investigates and explains the nature and essential properties and relations of all beings, as such, or the principles and causes of being.

Odometrous: Serving to measure distance on a road.
orthodontic: Of or pertaining to orthodontics or orthodontia.
off-base: located outside a military base; as, off-base housing.

ovulate: To produce ova and discharge them from an ovary or ovarian follicle.
Opetide: Open time; -- applied to different things

Overturnable: Capable of being, or liable to be, overturned or subverted.

Oligarchist: An advocate or supporter of oligarchy.
othonna: A South African plant of the genus Othonna having smooth often fleshy leaves and heads of yellow flowers.
Obsequy: The last duty or service to a person, rendered after his death; hence, a rite or ceremony pertaining to burial; -- now used only in the plural.
Ovate-cylindraceous: Having a form intermediate between ovate and cylindraceous.

Occupy: To hold possession; to be an occupant.
Overget: To reach; to overtake; to pass.

Organoleptic: Making an impression upon an organ; plastic; -- said of the effect or impression produced by any substance on the organs of touch, taste, or smell, and also on the organism as a whole.

overstated: represented as greater than is true or reasonable; exaggerated; as, They made overstated accusations of corruption.

optionee: A person who holds an option to buy or sell a financial instrument.  See option.

Ophiomancy: Divination by serpents, as by their manner of eating, or by their coils.

Ostraciont: A fish of the genus Ostracion and allied genera.
off-duty: not performing or available for duties at the given moment; as, an off-duty policeman.  Oposite of on-duty, working, and on-the-job.

Oversupply: An excessive supply; a supply in excess of demand.
Orthorhombic: Noting the system of crystallization which has three unequal axes at right angles to each other; trimetric. See Crystallization.
Onondagas: A tribe of Indians formerly inhabiting what is now a part of the State of New York. They were the central or head tribe of the Five Nations.

Overspread: To be spread or scattered over.
off-the-shelf: Made in large quantities and intended to be used without modifications; -- similar to off-the-rack, but not restricted to clothing.  Opposite of custom-made, made-to-order, or one-of-a-kind.

Ontologist: One who is versed in or treats of ontology.
&Verbar;Ophiophagus: A genus of venomous East Indian snakes, which feed on other snakes. Ophiophagus elaps is said to be the largest and most deadly of poisonous snakes.
Orleans: A cloth made of worsted and cotton, -- used for wearing apparel.
Omniparity: Equality in every part; general equality.
&Verbar;Omnivora: A group of ungulate mammals including the hog and the hippopotamus.  The term is also sometimes applied to the bears, and to certain passerine birds.
Oblate: One of an association of priests or religious women who have offered themselves to the service of the church.  There are three such associations of priests, and one of women, called oblates.
Oxyrrhodine: A mixture of two parts of the oil of roses with one of the vinegar of roses.
Ought: Was or were under obligation to pay; owed.
Outlive: To live beyond, or longer than; to survive.
Offer: The act of offering, bringing forward, proposing, or bidding; a proffer; a first advance.
out-of-town: happening in or being of another town or city; as, an out-of-town tryout.
overemphasize: to emphasize excessively; to place excessive emphasis on.
Oscan: Of or pertaining to the Osci, a primitive people of Campania, a province of ancient Italy.
Outshoot: To exceed or excel in shooting; to shoot beyond.
Orsellinic: Pertaining to, or designating, an organic acid obtained by a partial decomposition of orsellic acid as a white crystalline substance, and related to protocatechuic acid.
Overblow: To blow away; to dissipate by wind, or as by wind.
Octoic: Pertaining to, derived from, or resembling, octane; -- used specifically, to designate any one of a group of acids, the most important of which is called caprylic acid.
otherworldly: existing outside of or not in accordance with nature.
Oared: Furnished with oars; -- chiefly used in composition; as, a four-oared boat.
orthodontia: The treatment of the teeth so as to make the teeth align properly within the mouth, usually involving the wearing of braces and sometimes oral surgery.
Ozonoscopic: Serving to indicate the presence or the amount of ozone.
Orchotomy: The operation of cutting out or removing a testicle by the knife; castration.
Outset: A setting out, starting, or beginning.
Outsettler: One who settles at a distance, or away, from others.
Ornithology: That branch of zoölogy which treats of the natural history of birds and their classification.
Outreckon: To exceed in reckoning or computation.
Octahedral: Having eight faces or sides; of, pertaining to, or formed in, octahedrons; as, octahedral cleavage; an octahedral crystal.
ozone paper: Paper coated with starch and potassium iodine, also called starch-iodide paper. It turns blue when exposed to ozone.
Ophiomorphous: Having the form of a serpent.
Osteopterygious: Having bones in the fins, as certain fishes.
Operator: One who, or that which, operates or produces an effect.
one-step: an early ballroom dance, precursor to the foxtrot.
Ovotesttis: An organ which produces both ova and spermatozoids; an hermaphrodite gland.
Overdrown: To wet or drench to excess.
Oxalic: Pertaining to, derived from, or contained in, sorrel, or oxalis; specifically, designating an acid found in, and characteristic of, oxalis, and also certain plant of the Buckwheat family.
Overexcitement: Excess of excitement; the state of being overexcited.
Outwin: To win a way out of.
Obliquation: The act of becoming oblique; a turning to one side; obliquity; as, the obliquation of the eyes.
olm: A European cave-dwelling aquatic salamander (Proteus anguinus) with permanent external gills.
\u0152dematous: Pertaining to, or of the nature of, edema; affected with edema.
Outwit: The faculty of acquiring wisdom by observation and experience, or the wisdom so acquired; -- opposed to inwit.
Obreptitious: Done or obtained by surprise; with secrecy, or by concealment of the truth.
Observantine: One of a branch of the Order of Franciscans, who profess to adhere more strictly than the Conventuals to the intention of the founder, especially as to poverty; -- called also Observants.
Overplus: That which remains after a supply, or beyond a quantity proposed; surplus.
Obsidional: Of or pertaining to a siege.
onagon: A form of drum used by the Chippewa indians.
Overply: To ply to excess; to exert with too much vigor; to overwork.
Orthophony: The art of correct articulation; voice training.
Odometry: Measurement of distances by the odometer.
Ontogenesis: The history of the individual development of an organism; the sequence of events involved in the development of an organism; the history of the evolution of the germ; the development of an individual organism, -- in distinction from phylogeny, or evolution of the tribe.  Called also henogenesis, henogeny.
Oxymuriatic: Pertaining to, or consisting of, oxygen and muriatic acid, that is, hydrochloric acid.
Overtitle: To give too high a title to.
Oncograph: An instrument for registering the changes observable with an oncometer.
Open-air: Taking place in the open air; outdoor; as, an open-air game or meeting.
Oxyphenol: A phenol, C6H4(OH)2, produced by the distillation of catechin; called also oxyphenic acid, and now pyrocatechin.
Oxbow: A frame of wood, bent into the shape of the letter U, and embracing an ox's neck as a kind of collar, the upper ends passing through the bar of the yoke; also, anything so shaped, as a bend in a river.
Oso-berry: The small, blueblack, drupelike fruit of the Nuttallia cerasiformis, a shrub of Oregon and California, belonging to the Cherry tribe of Rosaceæ.
Obimbricate: Imbricated, with the overlapping ends directed downward.
Oppress: To impose excessive burdens upon; to overload; hence, to treat with unjust rigor or with cruelty.
oreo: A confection consisting of a white cream filling sandwiched between two chocolate cookies.
Opposeless: Not to be effectually opposed; irresistible.
Occasionality: Quality or state of being occasional; occasional occurrence.
Ovipositing: The depositing of eggs, esp. by insects.
Ocarina: A kind of small simple wind instrument.
Orchestrion: A large music box imitating a variety of orchestral instruments.
Overshot: Having the upper teeth projecting beyond the lower; -- said of the jaws of some dogs.
Occasional: Occuring at times, but not constant, regular, or systematic; made or happening as opportunity requires or admits; casual; incidental; as, occasional remarks, or efforts.
Oreoselin: A white crystalline substance which is obtained indirectly from the root of an umbelliferous plant (Imperatoria Oreoselinum), and yields resorcin on decomposition.
Overofficious: Too busy; too ready to intermeddle; too officious.
Obtrusionist: One who practices or excuses obtrusion.
Overrule: To be superior or supreme in rulling or controlling; as, God rules and overrules.
Overshoe: A shoe that is worn over another for protection from wet or for extra warmth; esp., an India-rubber shoe; a galosh.
Opinionative: Unduly attached to one's own opinions; opinionated.
Office wire: Copper wire with a strong but light insulation, used in wiring houses, etc.
Overmaster: To overpower; to subdue; to vanquish; to govern.
outward-bound: travelling away from a port or station; as, outward-bound ships.  Opposite of inward-bound or inbound.
Occecation: The act of making blind, or the state of being blind.
Obtundent: A substance which sheathes a part, or blunts irritation, usually some bland, oily, or mucilaginous matter; -- nearly the same as demulcent.
outfox: To defeat or gain an advantage over (an antagonist) by clever stratagems; to outwit; to outmaneuver; to outsmart.
Onto: On the top of; upon; on. See On to, under On, prep.
Optigraph: A telescope with a diagonal eyepiece, suspended vertically in gimbals by the object end beneath a fixed diagonal plane mirror.  It is used for delineating landscapes, by means of a pencil at the eye end which leaves the delineation on paper.
Odize: To charge with od. See Od.
Outlearn: To excel or surpass in learing.
Ods: A corruption of God's; -- formerly used in oaths and ejaculatory phrases.
Oswego tea: An American aromatic herb (Monarda didyma), with showy, bright red, labiate flowers.
Ortho\u00ebpic: Of or pertaining to orthoëpy, or correct pronunciation.
Overanxiety: The state of being overanxious; excessive anxiety.
Oxalis: A genus of plants, mostly herbs, with acid-tasting trifoliolate or multifoliolate leaves; -- called also wood sorrel.
Odd: Not paired with another, or remaining over after a pairing; without a mate; unmatched; single; as, an odd shoe; an odd glove.
Ostentator: One fond of display; a boaster.
Oddment: An odd thing, or one that is left over, disconnected, fragmentary, or the like; something that is separated or disconnected from its fellows;
Outbabble: To utter foolishly or excessively; to surpass in babbling.
Omissible: Capable of being omitted; that may be omitted.
Onward: Toward a point before or in front; forward; progressively; as, to move onward.
one-third: one of three equal parts of a divisible whole.
opportunistic: taking immediate advantage, often unethically, of any circumstance of possible benefit; practising opportunism.
Overmeasure: Excessive measure; the excess beyond true or proper measure; surplus.
Obligatory: Binding in law or conscience; imposing duty or obligation; requiring performance or forbearance of some act; -- often followed by on or upon; as, obedience is obligatory on a soldier.
Oculiform: In the form of an eye; resembling an eye; as, an oculiform pebble.
Otides: A suborder of terrestrial game birds of the Old World and Australia, including the bustards.
Outnoise: To exceed in noise; to surpass in noisiness.
Opisthotic: The inferior and posterior of the three elements forming the periotic bone.
Oersted: The C. G. S. unit of magnetic reluctance or resistance, equal to the reluctance of a centimeter cube of air (or vacuum) between parallel faces.  Also, a reluctance in which unit magnetomotive force sets up unit flux.
Opaqueness: The state or quality of being impervious to light; opacity.
overrating: a calculation that results in an estimate that is too high.
Overhand: In an overhand manner or style.
Opinionist: One fond of his own notions, or unduly attached to his own opinions.
outreach: The act of reaching out; an effort to build connections from one person or group to another; as, the Police Department insituted a community outreach program.
Oxamic: Pertaining to, or designating, an acid NH2.CO.CO.HO obtained as a fine crystalline powder, intermediate between oxalic acid and oxamide. Its ammonium salt is obtained by boiling oxamide with ammonia.
oxyacetylene: Of or pertaining to a mixture of oxygen and actylene; as, an oxyacetylene torch.
Ornithorhynchus: A genus of monotremes including the platypus (Ornithorhyncus anatinus).  See Duck mole, under Duck.
Orthodromics: The art of sailing in a direct course, or on the arc of a great circle, which is the shortest distance between any two points on the surface of the globe; great-circle sailing; orthodromy.
omega: The last letter of the Greek alphabet. See Alpha.
Oppugner: One who opposes or attacks; that which opposes.
open-minded: Ready to entertain new ideas.  Contrasted with closed-minded.
Oblique: To deviate from a perpendicular line; to move in an oblique direction.
outpower: To excel in power; to overpover.
opencut: worked from the exposed surface; -- of mines and mining; as, opencut mining.
Omniprevalent: Prevalent everywhere or in all things.
Orient: To define the position of, in relation to the orient or east; hence, to ascertain the bearings of.
onchocerciasis: An infection with nematodes of the genus Onchocerca, especially Onchocerca volvulus. Oppositisepalous: Placed in front of a sepal.
Oligosiderite: A meteorite characterized by the presence of but a small amount of metallic iron.
Okra: An annual plant (Abelmoschus esculentus syn. Hibiscus esculentus), whose green pods, abounding in nutritious mucilage, are much used for soups, stews, or pickles; gumbo.
Oddness: The state of being odd, or not even.
Oleone: An oily liquid, obtained by distillation of calcium oleate, and probably consisting of the ketone of oleic acid.
Oxysalt: A salt of an oxyacid, as a sulphate.
Opelet: A bright-colored European actinian (Anemonia sulcata, syn. Anthea sulcata); -- so called because it does not retract its tentacles.
Organology: The science of organs or of anything considered as an organic structure.
Owner: One who owns; a rightful proprietor; one who has the legal or rightful title, whether he is the possessor or not.
Outfield: Arable land which has been or is being exhausted. See Infield, 1.
&Verbar;Ostracoidea: An order of Entomostraca possessing hard bivalve shells.  They are of small size, and swim freely about.  Now usually written Ostracoda.
Oathbreaking: The violation of an oath; perjury.
Oral: Uttered by the mouth, or in words; spoken, not written; verbal; as, oral traditions; oral testimony; oral law.
&Verbar;Olea: A genus of trees including the olive.
Odible: Fitted to excite hatred; hateful; odious.
Overfree: Free to excess; too liberal; too familiar.
Odinism: Worship of Odin; broadly, the Teutonic heathenism.
Overempty: To make too empty; to exhaust.
Orbitosphenoid: Of or pertaining to the sphenoid bone and the orbit, or to the orbitosphenoid bone.
Ornithic: Of or pertaining to birds; as, ornithic fossils.
Objectionable: Liable to objection; likely to be objected to or disapproved of; offensive; as, objectionable words.
&Verbar;Opisthomi: An order of eellike fishes having the scapular arch attached to the vertebræ, but not connected with the skull.
Ology: A colloquial or humorous name for any science or branch of knowledge.
Old-gentlemanly: Pertaining to an old gentleman, or like one.
Optatively: In an optative manner; with the expression of desire.
Outbounds: The farthest or exterior bounds; extreme limits; boundaries.
Offtake: Act of taking off; specif., the taking off or purchase of goods.
Orthostade: A chiton, or loose, ungirded tunic, falling in straight folds.
Orgiastic: Pertaining to, or of the nature of, orgies.
Orbitolites: A genus of living Foraminifera, forming broad, thin, circular disks, containing numerous small chambers.
Oxlike: Characteristic of, or like, an ox.
Osteologer: One versed in osteology; an osteologist.
Outsentry: A sentry who guards the entrance or approach to a place; an outguard.
Otology: The branch of science which treats of the ear and its diseases.
orthogamy: Direct fertilization in plants, as when the pollen fertilizing the ovules comes from the stamens of the same blossom; -- opposed to heterogamy.
Odal: Noting, or pert. to, odal land or ownership.
Oscitation: The act of yawning or gaping.
Overthrow: The act of overthrowing; the state of being overthrown; ruin.
Oxybutyric: Hydroxybutyric; designating any one of a group of metameric acids ((C3H6.OH).CO2H).
Ovate-lanceolate: Having a form intermediate between ovate and lanceolate.
Outwork: A minor defense constructed beyond the main body of a work, as a ravelin, lunette, hornwork, etc.
Oviparous: Producing young from eggs; as, an oviparous animal, in which the egg is generally separated from the animal, and hatched after exclusion; -- opposed to viviparous.
Overwrest: To wrest or force from the natural or proper position.
Overperch: To perch upon; to fly over.
Oyster-green: A green membranous seaweed (Ulva) often found growing on oysters but common on stones, piles, etc.
Oscillatory: Moving, or characterized by motion, backward and forward like a pendulum; swinging; oscillating; vibratory; as, oscillatory motion.
orthodontics: A branch of dentistry specializing in the treatment of the teeth so as to make the teeth align properly within the mouth; it usually involves fitting a patient with braces and sometimes oral surgery.
Obligatorily: In an obligatory manner; by reason of obligation.
Onomatechny: Prognostication by the letters of a name.
Opulent: Having a large estate or property; wealthy; rich; affluent; as, an opulent city; an opulent citizen.
&Verbar;Obiter: In passing; incidentally; by the way.
overappraisal: an appraisal that is too high.
Opalize: To convert into opal, or a substance like opal.
&Verbar;Ophidia: The suborder of reptiles which includes the serpents; called also Serpentes.
Overset: An upsetting; overturn; overthrow; as, the overset of a carriage.
Orthospermous: Having the seeds straight, as in the fruits of some umbelliferous plants; -- opposed to cœlospermous.
&Verbar;Obelion: The region of the skull between the two parietal foramina where the closure of the sagittal suture usually begins.
Olivaceous: Resembling the olive; of the color of the olive; olive-green.
Opianic: Of, pertaining to, or designating, an organic acid obtained by the oxidation of narcotine.
oversimplify: to simplify excessively so as to distort or misrepresent; -- of facts, assertions, or communications; as, Don't oversimplify the rules.
Octagynous: Having eight pistils or styles; octogynous.
Ornithoidichnite: A fossil track resembling that of a bird.
Outpace: To outgo; to move faster than; to leave behind.
Orphan: To cause to become an orphan; to deprive of parents.
Organophyly: The tribal history of organs, -- a branch of morphophyly.
Obliquity: The condition of being oblique; deviation from a right line; deviation from parallelism or perpendicularity; the amount of such deviation; divergence; as, the obliquity of the ecliptic to the equator.
O\u00f6genesis: The development, or mode of origin, of the ova.
Olympianism: Worship of the Olympian gods, esp. as a dominant cult or religion.
Openbill: A bird of the genus Anastomus, allied to the stork; -- so called because the two parts of the bill touch only at the base and tip. One species inhabits India, another Africa. Called also open-beak. See Illust. (m), under Beak.
Overexquisite: Too exquisite; too exact or nice; too careful.
Ostrogothic: Of or pertaining to the Ostrogoths.
Ovicell: One of the dilatations of the body wall of Bryozoa in which the ova sometimes undergo the first stages of their development. See Illust. of Chilostoma.
&Verbar;Olusatrum: An umbelliferous plant, the common Alexanders of Western Europe (Smyrnium Olusatrum).
&Verbar;Ostracea: A division of bivalve mollusks including the oysters and allied shells.
Outstrike: To strike out; to strike faster than.
Overtrow: To be too trustful or confident; to trust too much.
Observership: The office or work of an observer.
Outgoing: The act or the state of going out.
opposer: One who opposes; an opponent; an antagonist; an adversary.
&Verbar;Octaemeron: A fast of eight days before a great festival.
&Verbar;Oscines: Singing birds; a group of the Passeres, having numerous syringeal muscles, conferring musical ability.
Over-story: The clearstory, or upper story, of a building.
otacoustic: An instrument to facilitate hearing, as an ear trumpet.
Oxbane: A poisonous bulbous plant (Buphane toxicaria) of the Cape of Good Hope.
optimize: To make as useful, effective, or functional as possible; as, to optimize the speed of a computer program.
Overdrive: To drive too hard, or far, or beyond strength.
opposed: characterized by active opposition; as, two bitterly opposing schools of thought.
Observation deck: A room or platform at a high point in a tall building with a broad view of the surrounding area.  It is often an outdoor platform, but is sometimes indoors in a room with large windows to accommodate viewing.
October: The tenth month of the year, containing thirty-one days.
oilstove: A stove that burns oil (such as kerosine) for heating or cooking.
obelisk: An upright, four-sided pillar, gradually tapering as it rises, and terminating in a pyramid called pyramidion.  It is ordinarily monolithic.  Egyptian obelisks are commonly covered with hieroglyphic writing from top to bottom.
Overflowing: An overflow; that which overflows; exuberance; copiousness.
Outwrite: To exceed or excel in writing.
Orchidales: An order of plants with irregular flowers having minute seeds, and including the families Orchidaceae and Burmanniaceae.
Organogenesis: The origin and development of organs in animals and plants.
Omphacine: Of, pertaining to, or expressed from, unripe fruit; as, omphacine oil.
&Verbar;Obelus: A mark [thus —, or ÷]; -- so called as resembling a needle.  In old MSS. or editions of the classics, it marks suspected passages or readings.
Overaction: Performance to excess; exaggerated or excessive action.
osmometer: An instrument for measuring the amount of osmotic action in different liquids.
Our: Of or pertaining to us; belonging to us; as, our country; our rights; our troops; our endeavors. See I.

Overbrow: To hang over like a brow; to impend over.
Overshadow: To throw a shadow, or shade, over; to darken; to obscure.
Overestimate: An estimate that is too high; as, an overestimate of the vote.
Omniscient: Having universal knowledge; knowing all things; infinitely knowing or wise; as, the omniscient God.
Overburn: To burn too much; to be overzealous.
Oxidable: Capable of being converted into an oxide.
osmosis: The tendency in fluids to mix, or become equably diffused, when in contact. It was first observed between fluids of differing densities, and as taking place through a membrane or an intervening porous structure.  An older term for the phenomenon was Osmose.
Opalescence: A reflection of a milky or pearly light from the interior of a mineral, as in the moonstone; the state or quality of being opalescent.
Osteogenesis: The formation or growth of bone.
Onyx: Chalcedony in parallel layers of different shades of color.  It is used for making cameos, the figure being cut in one layer with the next as a ground.
Oblation: The act of offering, or of making an offering.
Oasis: A fertile or green spot in a waste or desert, esp. in a sandy desert, where the water table approaches the surface.
Outlawry: The act of outlawing; the putting a man out of the protection of law, or the process by which a man (as an absconding criminal) is deprived of that protection.
optimal: Best possible; most desirable; optimum; as, the optimal concentration of a drug.
Organific: Making an organic or organized structure; producing an organism; acting through, or resulting from, organs.
Organically: In an organic manner; by means of organs or with reference to organic functions; hence, fundamentally.
Outcrop: To come out to the surface of the ground; -- said of strata.
Oversee: To see too or too much; hence, to be deceived.
Outlaw: A person excluded from the benefit of the law, or deprived of its protection.
off-day: A day when things go poorly; as, I guess this is one of my off-days.
&Verbar;Odalisque: A female slave or concubine in the harem of the Turkish sultan.
Obtruncate: To deprive of a limb; to lop.
Obscenity: That quality in words or things which presents what is offensive to chastity or purity of mind; obscene or impure lanquage or acts; moral impurity; lewdness; obsceneness; as, the obscenity of a speech, or a picture.
Oxygenation: The act or process of combining or of treating with oxygen; oxidation.
Oroheliograph: A camera for obtaining a circular panoramic view of the horizon.  The photographic plate is placed horizontally with a vertical lens above.  A mirror of peculiar shape reflects light from the entire horizon to the lens, by means of which it is focused upon the plate.
Odd Fellow: A member of a secret order, or fraternity, styled the Independent Order of Odd Fellows, established for mutual aid and social enjoyment.
Orthogonal: Right-angled; rectangular; as, an orthogonal intersection of one curve with another.
Orcin: A colorless crystalline substance, C6H3.CH3.(OH)2, which is obtained from certain lichens (Roccella, Lecanora, etc.), also from extract of aloes, and artificially from certain derivatives of toluene.  It changes readily into orcein.
outpouring: An unrestrained expression (of emotion, feeling); as, an outpouring of grief over the death of Princess Diana.
Ochreate: Wearing or furnished with an ochrea or legging; wearing boots; booted.
Owlet: A small owl; especially, the European species (Athene noctua), and the California flammulated owlet (Megascops flammeolus).
officialdom: The body of all people elected or appointed to administer a government, taken collectively.
Overtrade: To trade beyond one's capital; to buy goods beyond the means of paying for or selling them; to overstock the market.
Oncometer: An instrument for measuring the variations in size of the internal organs of the body, as the kidney, spleen, etc.
&Verbar;O\u00f6sporangium: An oögonium; also, a case containing oval or rounded spores of some other kind than oöspores.
Overload: An excessive load; the excess beyond a proper load.
Outcast: One who is cast out or expelled; an exile; one driven from home, society, or country; hence, often, a degraded person; a vagabond.
-ol: A suffix denoting that the substance in the name of which it appears belongs to the series of alcohols or hydroxyl derivatives, as ethanol, carbinol, phenol, glycerol, etc.  Such compounds contain the hydroxy radical (-OH).
Osculate: To kiss one another; to kiss.
Ornithologic: Of or pertaining to ornithology; as, her ornithological interests.
Ordovician: Of or pertaining to a division of the Silurian formation, corresponding in general to the Lower Silurian of most authors, exclusive of the Cambrian.
Oleander: A beautiful evergreen shrub (Nerium oleander) of the Dogbane family, having clusters of fragrant red, white, or pink flowers.  It is a native of the East Indies, but the red variety has become common in the south of Europe. Called also rosebay, rose laurel, and South-sea rose.
Oncost: In cost accounting, expenditure which is involved in the process of manufacture or the performance of work and which cannot be charged directly to any particular article manufactured or work done (as where different kinds of goods are produced), but must be allocated so that each kind of goods or work shall bear its proper share.
&Verbar;Ornithoscelida: A group of extinct Reptilia, intermediate in structure (especially with regard to the pelvis) between reptiles and birds.
Orthosilicic: Designating the form of silicic acid having the normal or highest number of hydroxyl groups.
Ovicular: Of or pertaining to an egg.
Ophidioid: Of or pertaining to the Ophidiidæ, a family of fishes which includes many slender species.
Organonymy: The designation or nomenclature of organs.
Overmatch: One superior in power; also, an unequal match; a contest in which one of the opponents is overmatched.
Option: The power of choosing; the right of choice or election; an alternative.
Outjest: To surpass in jesting; to drive out, or away, by jesting.
Outloose: A loosing from; an escape; an outlet; an evasion.
Overruling: Exerting controlling power; as, an overruling Providence.
Originality: The quality or state of being original.
Octofid: Cleft or separated into eight segments, as a calyx.
Oxamethylane: Methyl oxamate, obtained as a pearly white crystalline substance.
Obtain: To gain or have a firm footing; to be recognized or established; to become prevalent or general; to prevail; as, the custom obtains of going to the seashore in summer.
overblown: Having been given more publicity than warranted; having had ascribed more importance than was justified; as, an overblown medical discovery.
optical activity: the ability of a chemical compound to rotate the plane of plane-polarized light.  This is found only in chemicals whose molecular structure does not have a plane of symmetry, and is common in biochemical compounds.
Ovisac: A Graafian follicle; any sac containing an ovum or ova.
Overeat: To gnaw all over, or on all sides.
Objectable: Such as can be presented in opposition; that may be put forward as an objection.
one-hitter: A game in which a pitcher allows the opposing team only one hit.
Outring: To excel in volume of ringing sound; to ring louder than.
&Verbar;Ostosis: Bone formation; ossification. See Ectostosis, and Endostosis.
Overcloud: To cover or overspread with clouds; to becloud; to overcast.
Ophthalmometer: An instrument devised by Helmholtz for measuring the size of a reflected image on the convex surface of the cornea and lens of the eye, by which their curvature can be ascertained.
Obsign: To seal; to confirm, as by a seal or stamp.
Otoba fat: A colorless buttery substance obtained from the fruit of Myristica otoba, a species of nutmeg tree.
Oxeye: The oxeye daisy. See under Daisy.
Outsole: The outside sole of a boot or shoe.
opened: having the covering skin pulled back; -- used of mouth or eyes; as, his mouth slightly opened.  Opposite of closed.
Overpost: To post over; to pass over swiftly, as by post.
oscillograph: a device for making a record of the wave forms of fluctuating .
Outgrowth: That which grows out of, or proceeds from, anything; an excrescence; an offshoot; hence, a result or consequence.
Opalescent: Reflecting a milky or pearly light from the interior; having an opaline play of colors.
Overpeer: To peer over; to rise above.
Ozonometric: Pertaining to, or used for, the determination of the amount of ozone; of or relating to ozonometry.
Oversnow: To cover with snow, or as with snow.
Opium: The inspissated juice of the Papaver somniferum, or white poppy.
Offender: One who offends; one who violates any law, divine or human; a wrongdoer.
Obsequiously: In an obsequious manner; compliantly; fawningly.
Ordain: To set in order; to arrange according to rule; to regulate; to set; to establish.
Obtrude: To thrust one's self upon a company or upon attention; to intrude.
outlawed: contrary to or forbidden by law; banned; illicit; as, a member of an outlawed political party.
Omostegite: The part of the carapace of a crustacean situated behind the cervical groove.
orc: Any of several cetaceans, especialy the grampus (Grampus griseus) of the dolphin family.
one-horse: Drawn by one horse; having but a single horse; as, a one-horse carriage.
Outact: To do or beyond; to exceed in acting.
Omphalomancy: Divination by means of a child's navel, to learn how many children the mother may have.
Otto cycle: A four-stroke cycle for internal-combustion engines consisting of the following operations: First stroke, suction into cylinder of explosive charge, as of gas and air; second stroke, compression, ignition, and explosion of this charge; third stroke (the working stroke), expansion of the gases; fourth stroke, expulsion of the products of combustion from the cylinder.  This is the cycle invented by Beau de Rochas in 1862 and applied by Dr. Otto in 1877 in the Otto-Crossley gas engine, the first commercially successful internal-combustion engine made.
ostrich: A large bird of the genus Struthio, of which Struthio camelus of Africa is the best known species. It has long and very strong legs, adapted for rapid running; only two toes; a long neck, nearly bare of feathers; and short wings incapable of flight. The adult male is about eight feet high.
Overbow: To bend or bow over; to bend in a contrary direction.
Octodecimo: A book composed of sheets each of which is folded into eighteen leaves; hence; indicating more or less definitely a size of book, whose sheets are so folded; -- usually written 18mo or 18°, and called eighteenmo.
Oppositeness: The quality or state of being opposite.
Overskip: To skip or leap over; to treat with indifference.
Outstreet: A street remote from the center of a town.
Opisthobranchiate: Of or pertaining to the Opisthobranchiata.
Operose: Wrought with labor; requiring labor; hence, tedious; wearisome.
Oleograph: The form or figure assumed by a drop of oil when placed upon water or some other liquid with which it does not mix.
on-key: In tune; striking or singing the proper notes.  Opposite of off-key.
Obovate: Inversely ovate; ovate with the narrow end downward; as, an obovate leaf.
Overcanopy: To cover as with a canopy.
Oppression: The act of oppressing, or state of being oppressed.
Orthometry: The art or practice of constructing verses correctly; the laws of correct versification.
Outbuild: To exceed in building, or in durability of building.
Offerable: Capable of being offered; suitable or worthy to be offered.
oversimplified: simplified excessively so as to distort or misrepresent; -- of facts, assertions, or communications.  Contrasted with overcomplicated.
\u0152nanthylidene: A colorless liquid hydrocarbon, having a garlic odor; heptine.
Outpost: A post or station without the limits of a camp, or at a distance from the main body of an army, for observation of the enemy.
Olearia: A large genus of Australian evergreen shrubs or small trees with large daisylike flowers.
Ophthalmologist: One skilled in ophthalmology; an oculist.
Omniparient: Producing or bringing forth all things; all-producing.
Ovoid: A solid resembling an egg in shape.
Omer: A Hebrew measure, the tenth of an ephah. See Ephah.
Oxeyed: Having large, full eyes, like those of an ox.
Oreortyx: A genus of birds including the mountain quail of the western U. S.
Overbid: To bid or offer beyond, or in excess of.
Overcarry: To carry too far; to carry beyond the proper point.
Openly: In an open manner; publicly; not in private; without secrecy.
&Verbar;O\u00f6gonium: A special cell in certain cryptogamous plants containing oöspheres, as in the rockweeds (Fucus), and the orders Vaucherieæ and Peronosporeæ.
Ophioglossaceae: A natural family of succulent ferns cosmopolitan in distribution.
Ovidian: Of or pertaining to the Latin poet Ovid; resembling the style of Ovid.
&Verbar;Ocellus: A little eye; a minute simple eye found in many invertebrates.
&Verbar;Ophiurioidea: A class of star-shaped echinoderms having a disklike body, with slender, articulated arms, which are not grooved beneath and are often very fragile; -- called also Ophiuroida and Ophiuridea. See Illust. under Brittle star.
Ocypodian: One of a tribe of crabs which live in holes in the sand along the seashore, and run very rapidly, -- whence the name.
overfill: To fill to excess; to surcharge.
Obrogate: To annul indirectly by enacting a new and contrary law, instead of by expressly abrogating or repealing the old one.
Overmast: To furnish (a vessel) with too long or too heavy a mast or masts.
Ovariole: One of the tubes of which the ovaries of most insects are composed.
Overcautious: Too cautious; cautious or prudent to excess.
object file: A computer program which has been translated into machine language by a compiler and assembler, but not yet linked into an executable program; sometimes called an obj file, because its file name typically has the extension “obj” .
occupied: Engaged; in use; being used by a person and not free for use by someone else; as, the wc is occupied.  Opposite of free, available, and unoccupied.
Orangeism: Attachment to the principles of the society of Orangemen; the tenets or practices of the Orangemen.
Ommateal: Of or pertaining to an ommateum.
Ordurous: Of or pertaining to ordure; filthy.
Okinawa: the largest island of the central Ryukyu Islands.
Osteotome: Strong nippers or a chisel for dividing bone.
online: connected by a  communications line to a computer.  Opposite of off-line.
Oldness: The state or quality of being old; old age.
Observing: Giving particular attention; habitually attentive to what passes; observant{1}; as, an observing person; an observing mind.
&Verbar;Orlo: A wind instrument of music in use among the Spaniards.
Off: The side of the field that is on the right of the wicket keeper.
opposite: Placed over against; standing or situated over against or in front; facing; -- often with to; as, a house opposite to the Exchange; the concert hall and the state theater stood opposite each other on the plaza.
Overglaze: Applied over the glaze; -- said of enamel paintings, which sometimes are seen to project from the surface of the ware.
ozonic: Pertaining to, resembling, or containing, ozone.
Obtuseness: State or quality of being obtuse.
out-migration: migration out of country or territory; emigration.
Omophagic: Eating raw flesh; using uncooked meat as food; as, omophagic feasts, rites.
Oculist: One skilled in treating diseases of the eye.
Occurrence: A coming or happening; as, the occurence of a railway collision.
office-bearer: A person who holds an office; an officeholder.
Owenite: A follower of Robert Owen, who tried to reorganize society on a socialistic basis, and established an industrial community on the Clyde, Scotland, and, later, a similar one in Indiana.
Ovulist: A believer in the theory (called encasement theory), current during the last century, that the egg was the real animal germ, and that at the time of fecundation the spermatozoa simply gave the impetus which caused the unfolding of the egg, in which all generations were inclosed one within the other. Also called ovist.
Outrush: To rush out; to issue, or run out, forcibly.
Ombrometer: An instrument for measuring the rain that falls; a rain gauge.
obsidian: A kind of glass produced by volcanoes.  It is usually of a black color, and opaque, except in thin splinters.
Oriole: Any one of various species of Old World singing birds of the family Oriolidæ.  They are usually conspicuously colored with yellow and black.  The European or golden oriole (Oriolus galbula, or Oriolus oriolus) has a very musical flutelike note.
&Verbar;Ostracodermi: A suborder of fishes of which Ostracion is the type.
operations: financial transactions at a brokerage; having to do with the execution of trades and keeping customer records.
Owing: Had or held under obligation of paying; due.
off-street: Not performed on the streets; as, off-street parking; off-street unloading of vehicles.  Opposite of on-street.
octagonal: Having eight sides and eight angles.
Ogygian: Of or pertaining to Ogyges, a mythical king of ancient Attica, or to a great deluge in Attica in his days; hence, primeval; of obscure antiquity.
Orotund: Characterized by fullness, clearness, strength, and smoothness; ringing and musical; -- said of the voice or manner of utterance.
Oblige: To attach, as by a bond.
Overbuilt: Having too many buildings; as, an overbuilt part of a town.
Outtravel: To exceed in speed or distance traveled.
Obsequiousness: The quality or state of being obsequious.
Overhold: To hold or value too highly; to estimate at too dear a rate.
Ornitholite: The fossil remains of a bird.
over: Excessively; too much or too greatly; -- chiefly used in composition; as, overwork, overhasty, overeager, overanxious, overreact, overcook.
Occupant: One who occupies, or takes possession; one who has the actual use or possession, or is in possession, of a thing; as, the occupant of the apartment is not at home.
Outgoer: One who goes out or departs.
Orthoscopic: Giving an image in correct or normal proportions; giving a flat field of view; as, an orthoscopic eyepiece.
oil patch: A geographical region from which petroleum is extracted.
Overshine: To shine over or upon; to illumine.
oscilloscope: An electronic measuring instrument which provides a visual representation of the time variation of electrical quantities, such as voltage or current.  It may be used to measure the shape of a voltage pulse or the frequency of an oscillating voltage.  It can also be used to measure properties of other physical variables, such as sound or light intensity, if they can be translated into electrical voltage or current.
Orarian: Of or pertaining to a coast.
Outvote: To exceed in the number of votes given; to defeat by votes.
Organography: A description of the organs of animals or plants.
&Verbar;Otis: A genus of birds including certain of the bustards.
oxyacetylene torch: A torch designed to mix oxygen and actylene at its tip, to create a very hot flame for welding, cutting steel, and other metal working.
odometrical: Of or pertaining to the odometer, or to measurements made with it.
Ovicyst: The pouch in which incubation takes place in some Tunicata.
Ogle: An amorous side glance or look.
Obnoxious: Subject; liable; exposed; answerable; amenable; -- with to.
Ourselves: An emphasized form of the pronoun of the first person plural; -- used as a subject, usually with we; also, alone in the predicate, in the nominative or the objective case.
Osteotomy: The dissection or anatomy of bones; osteology.
offset printing: A printing technique in which a lithographic image on an inked metal or stone plate is transferred first to a rubber sheet (usually on a cylinder) before transfer to the paper.  Called also offset lithography.
Occasive: Of or pertaining to the setting sun; falling; descending; western.
Overturn: The act off overturning, or the state of being overturned or subverted; overthrow; as, an overturn of parties.
Ophiodontidae: A natural family of fishes closely related to greenlings (fish of the genus Hexagrammos).
Oviduct: A tube, or duct, for the passage of ova from the ovary to the exterior of the animal or to the part where further development takes place.  In mammals the oviducts are also called Fallopian tubes.
Ontogenetic: Of or pertaining to ontogenesis; as, ontogenetic phenomena.
obliging: Putting under obligation; disposed to oblige or do favors; hence, helpful; civil; kind.
Obediential: According to the rule of obedience.
ornament: To adorn; to deck; to embellish; to beautify; as, to ornament a room, or a city.
Overcast: To cast or cover over; hence, to cloud; to darken.
Oneberry: The herb Paris. See Herb Paris, under Herb.
Officeholder: One who holds an office; an officer, particularly one in the civil service; a placeman.
Overdose: Too great a dose; an excessive dose.
orchestrate: to write an orchestra score for; -- of a musical composition.
&Verbar;Ormuzd: The good principle, or being, of the ancient Persian religion; same as Ormazd. See also Ahriman.
Overtop: To rise above the top of; to exceed in height; to tower above.
Oozy: Miry; containing soft mud; resembling ooze; as, the oozy bed of a river.
Ordonnance: The disposition of the parts of any composition with regard to one another and the whole.
Overnight: The fore part of the night last past; the previous evening.
Orgy: A frantic revel; drunken revelry. See Orgies
&Verbar;Ommateum: A compound eye, as of insects and crustaceans.
oil tanker: A ship having large compartments, designed to transport crude oil over the ocean.
Otoscopeic: Of or pertaining to the otoscope or to otoscopy.
Oath: A solemn affirmation or declaration, made with a reverent appeal to God for the truth of what is affirmed.
Optation: The act of optating; a wish.
osteoclast: Same as myeloplax, a large multinucleate cell within the bone, which functions in the absroption and removal of bone tissue.
Opination: The act of thinking; a supposition.
Ode: A short poetical composition proper to be set to music or sung; a lyric poem; esp., now, a poem characterized by sustained noble sentiment and appropriate dignity of style.
Obstruction: The act of obstructing, or state of being obstructed.
Obstacle: That which stands in the way, or opposes; anything that hinders progress; a hindrance; an obstruction, physical or moral.
&Verbar;Ophidion: The typical genus of ophidioid fishes. [Written also Ophidium.] See Illust. under Ophidioid.
Outmeasure: To exceed in measure or extent; to measure more than.
oil slick: A layer of oil floating on water; -- usually petroleum or fuel oil which has leaked from a ship.
Obituarily: In the manner of an obituary.
Oviducal: Of or pertaining to oviducts; as, oviducal glands.
Overshake: To shake over or away; to drive away; to disperse.
Overheat: To heat to excess; to superheat.
-oma: A suffix used in medical terms to denote a morbid condition of some part, usually some kind of tumor; as in fibroma, glaucoma.
one-edged: Having only one sharp edge; single-edged; -- of cutting instruments, mostly swords and razor blades.  Opposed to double-edged.
Opsiometer: An instrument for measuring the limits of distinct vision in different individuals, and thus determiming the proper focal length of a lens for correcting imperfect sight.
over-the-counter: able to be sold legally without a doctor's prescription; -- of medicinal drugs.  Contrasted with prescription.
opianine: An alkaloid (C22H23NO7) found in small quantity in opium.  It is identical with narcotine.  It is present in amounts up to 11% in Papaver somniferum, and is used clinically as an antitussive.
Overwear: Clothing worn over the ordinary indoor clothing, as overcoats, wraps, etc.
Outspoken: Speaking, or spoken, freely, openly, candidly, or boldly; as, an outspoken man; an outspoken rebuke.
Offenseful: Causing offense; displeasing; wrong; as, an offenseful act.
Oarlock: The notch, fork, or other device on the gunwale of a boat, in which the oar rests, and that holds the oar in place and acts as a fulcrum for rowing.  Certain oarlocks are designed for use with oars having attached swivels, which insert into the oarlock and provide a firm pivot.  Same as Rowlock{1}.
Osteocranium: The bony cranium, as distinguished from the cartilaginous cranium.
Orpharion: An old instrument of the lute or cittern kind.
oncotomy: The opening of an abscess, or the removal of a tumor, with a cutting instrument.
Otocyst: An auditory cyst or vesicle; one of the simple auditory organs of many invertebrates, containing a fluid and otoliths; also, the embryonic vesicle from which the parts of the internal ear of vertebrates are developed.
Optional: Involving an option; depending on the exercise of an option; left to one's discretion or choice; allowed but not compulsory; as, optional studies; it is optional with you to go or stay.
Onslaught: An attack; an onset; esp., a furious or murderous attack or assault.
Ouch: A socket or bezel holding a precious stone; hence, a jewel or ornament worn on the person.
ongoing: Occurring at present; progressing; in progress; continuing; not past, completed, or future; as, an ongoing petition drive; an ongoing effort.
Ostracean: Any one of a family of bivalves, of which the oyster is the type.
Osteophone: An instrument for transmission of auditory vibrations through the bones of the head, so as to be appreciated as sounds by persons deaf from causes other than those affecting the nervous apparatus of hearing.
Open: To unclose; to form a hole, breach, or gap; to be unclosed; to be parted.
Occupier: One who occupies, or has possession.
Orthopinacoid: A name given to the two planes in the monoclinic system which are parallel to the vertical and orthodiagonal axes.
Oaf: Originally, an elf's child; a changeling left by fairies or goblins; hence, a deformed or foolish child; a simpleton; an idiot.
