Olecranon: The large process at the proximal end of the ulna which projects behind the articulation with the humerus and forms the bony prominence of the elbow.
Ondatra: A genus of rodents including the muskrat (Ondatra zibethica).
Orchidology: The branch of botany which treats of orchids.
Out-Herod: To surpass (Herod) in violence or wickedness; to exceed in any vicious or offensive particular.  Compare outpope the Pope.
Octameter:
A verse containing eight feet; as, --

Deep" in|to" the | dark"ness | peer"ing, | long" I | stood" there | wond'"ring, | fear"ing.
Oat: A well-known cereal grass (Avena sativa), and its edible grain,  used as food and fodder; -- commonly used in the plural and in a collective sense.
&Verbar;Ochlesis: A general morbid condition induced by the crowding together of many persons, esp. sick persons, under one roof.
Oxidizer: An agent employed in oxidation, or which facilitates or brings about combination with oxygen; as, nitric acid, chlorine, bromine, etc., are strong oxidizers.
Origan: A genus of aromatic labiate plants, including the sweet marjoram (Origanum Marjorana) and the wild marjoram (Origanum vulgare).
Oleate: A salt of oleic acid. Some oleates, as the oleate of mercury, are used in medicine by way of inunction.
Ornithichnite: The footmark of a bird occurring in strata of stone.
Orfgild: Restitution for cattle; a penalty for taking away cattle.
Officiary: Of or pertaining to an office or an officer; official.
Ornithologist: One skilled in ornithology; a student of ornithology; one who describes birds.
Outreign: To go beyond in reigning; to reign through the whole of, or longer than.
Oversum: A sum or quantity over; surplus.
&Verbar;Ondoyant: Wavy; having the surface marked by waves or slightly depressed furrows; as, ondoyant glass.
Oleometer: An instrument for ascertaining the weight and purity of oil; an elaiometer.
Overlogical: Excessively logical; adhering too closely to the forms or rules of logic.
&Verbar;Otorrh\u0153a: A flow or running from the ear, esp. a purulent discharge.
Opinionated: Stiff in opinion; firmly or unduly adhering to one's own opinion or to preconceived notions; obstinate in opinion.
&Verbar;Oxymoron: A figure in which an epithet of a contrary signification is added to a word; e. g., cruel kindness; laborious idleness.
Opaline: An opaline variety of yellow chalcedony.
&Verbar;Octapla: A portion of the Old Testament prepared by Origen in the 3d century, containing the Hebrew text and seven Greek versions of it, arranged in eight parallel columns.
Outskirt: A part remote from the center, and near the outer edge; border; -- usually in the plural; as, the outskirts of a town.
Outport: A harbor or port at some distance from the chief town or seat of trade.
Own: To hold as property; to have a legal or rightful title to; to be the proprietor or possessor of; to possess; as, to own a house.
Obcompressed: Compressed or flattened antero-posteriorly, or in a way opposite to the usual one.
Outboard: Beyond or outside of the lines of a vessel's bulwarks or hull; in a direction from the hull or from the keel; -- opposed to inboard; as, outboard rigging; swing the davits outboard.
Objectively: In the manner or state of an object; as, a determinate idea objectively in the mind.
Outbuilding: A building separate from, and subordinate to, the main house; an outhouse.
Orach: A genus (Atriplex) of herbs or low shrubs of the Goosefoot family, most of them with a mealy surface.
Orchilla weed: The lichen from which archil is obtained. See Archil.
Oligarch: A member of an oligarchy; one of the rulers in an oligarchical government.
organzine: A kind of double thrown silk of very fine texture, that is, silk twisted like a rope with different strands, so as to increase its strength.
Overlinger: To cause to linger; to detain too long.
&Verbar;Organista: Any one of several South American wrens, noted for the sweetness of their song.
Outdweller: One who holds land in a parish, but lives elsewhere.
Ostentatious: Fond of, or evincing, ostentation; unduly conspicuous; pretentious; boastful.
Octylic: Pertaining to, derived from, or containing, octyl; as, octylic ether.
Occultation: The hiding of a heavenly body from sight by the intervention of some other of the heavenly bodies; -- applied especially to eclipses of stars and planets by the moon, and to the eclipses of satellites of planets by their primaries.
Overlying: Lying over or upon something; as, overlying rocks.
Oryzomys: A genus of rodents including the rice rats.
Opodeldoc: A kind of plaster, said to have been invented by Mindererus, -- used for external injuries.
Onomatope: An imitative word; an onomatopoetic word.
Obreption: The act of creeping upon with secrecy or by surprise.
old-man-of-the-woods: An edible mild-tasting mushroom (Strobilomyces floccopus) found in coniferous woodlands of eastern North America.
Orbicular: Resembling or having the form of an orb; spherical; circular; orbiculate.
organometallic: Pertaining to, or denoting, any one of a series of compounds of certain metallic elements bound to organic radicals; such as, methylmercury, zinc methyl, sodium ethyl, etc.; formerly refered to as metalorganic.
Obscurantism: The system or the principles of the obscurants.
Otherwhile: At another time, or other times; sometimes; occasionally.
Olive: Approaching the color of the olive; of a peculiar dark brownish, yellowish, or tawny green.
overcompensate: to make excessive corrections for fear of making an error.
&Verbar;Odontotormae: An order of extinct toothed birds having the teeth in sockets, as in the genus Ichthyornis. See Ichthyornis.
out-of-school: not attending school and therefore free to work; as, opportunities for out-of-school youth.
\u0152nanthylate: A salt of oenanthylic acid; as, potassium œnanthylate.
Observable: Capable of being observed; discernible; noticeable.
&Verbar;Osphradium: The olfactory organ of some Mollusca.  It is connected with the organ of respiration.
Ownership: The state of being an owner; the right to own; exclusive right of possession; legal or just claim or title; proprietorship.
O\u00f6rial: A wild, bearded sheep inhabiting the Ladakh mountains. It is reddish brown, with a dark beard from the chin to the chest.
Outsail: To excel, or to leave behind, in sailing; to sail faster than.
Occidental: Of, pertaining to, or situated in, the occident, or west; western; -- opposed to oriental; as, occidental climates, or customs; an occidental planet.
&Verbar;Ornithopoda: An order of herbivorous dinosaurs with birdlike characteristics in the skeleton, esp. in the pelvis and hind legs, which in some genera had only three functional toes, and supported the body in walking as in Iguanodon. See Illust. in Appendix.
Odorous: Having or emitting an odor or scent, esp. a sweet odor; fragrant; sweet-smelling.
Orthodoxal: Pertaining to, or evincing, orthodoxy; orthodox.
Odontogeny: Generation, or mode of development, of the teeth.
Optate: To choose; to wish for; to desire.
Orthid: A brachiopod shell of the genus Orthis, and allied genera, of the family Orthidæ.
Outcompass: To exceed the compass or limits of.
Obligatoriness: The quality or state of being obligatory.
Operation: The act or process of operating; agency; the exertion of power, physical, mechanical, or moral.
oil well: A well{3} from which petroleum is or has been extracted; a well{3} drilled deeply into an oil-bearing geological formation specifically for the purpose of obtaining petroleum.
Otolith: One of the small bones or particles of calcareous or other hard substance in the internal ear of vertebrates, and in the auditory organs of many invertebrates; an ear stone.  Collectively, the otoliths are called ear sand and otoconite.
Osier: Made of osiers; composed of, or containing, osiers.
Orientalize: to render Oriental; to cause to conform to Oriental manners or conditions.
Overlook: To look down upon from a place that is over or above; to look over or view from a higher position; to be situated above, so as to command a view of; as, to overlook a valley from a hill; a hotel room that overlooks the marketplace.
Opisometer: An instrument with a revolving wheel for measuring a curved line, as on a map.
Odontology: The science which treats of the teeth, their structure and development.
octane: Any one of a group of metametric hydrocarbons (C8H18) of the methane (paraffin) series.  The most important is a colorless, volatile, inflammable liquid, found in petroleum, and a constituent of gasoline or ligroin.
Oregon grape: An evergreen species of barberry (Berberis Aquifolium), of Oregon and California; also, its roundish, blue-black berries.
Ostension: The showing of the sacrament on the altar in order that it may receive the adoration of the communicants.
&Verbar;Ostracion: A genus of plectognath fishes of the family Ostraciontidae having the body covered with solid, immovable, bony plates. It includes the trunkfishes (also called boxfish).
Oneidas: A tribe of Indians formerly inhabiting the region near Oneida Lake in the State of New York, and forming part of the Five Nations.  Remnants of the tribe now live in New York, Canada, and Wisconsin.
Orthopedic: Of, pertaining to, or employed in, orthopedics; relating to the prevention or cure of deformities of children, or, in general, of the human body at any age; as, orthopedic surgery; an orthopedic hospital.
Objectize: To make an object of; to regard as an object; to place in the position of an object.
on-street: at the sides of streets; as, on-street parking is prohibited at rush hour.  Opposite of off-street.
Omegoid: Having the form of the Greek capital letter Omega (Ω).
Overmost: Over the rest in authority; above all others; highest.
Orometer: An aneroid barometer having a second scale that gives the approximate elevation above sea level of the place where the observation is made.
Olio: A dish of stewed meat of different kinds.
Outdoors: Out of the house; out of doors; in the open air; abroad.
optical cable: a cable containing multiple optical fibers.
Ossification: The formation of bone; the process, in the growth of an animal, by which inorganic material (mainly lime salts) is deposited in cartilage or membrane, forming bony tissue; ostosis.
Osteocope: Pain in the bones; a violent fixed pain in any part of a bone.
Olid: Having a strong, disagreeable smell; fetid.
Oxygenic: Pertaining to, containing, or resembling, oxygen; producing oxygen.
Overpamper: To pamper excessively; to feed or dress too much.
off-color: humorously vulgar; mildly obscene; risque; as, an off-color joke.
opepe: A large African forest tree (Nauclea diderrichii) yielding a strong hard yellow to golden brown lumber; sometimes placed in genus Sarcocephalus, and then called Sarcocephalus diderrichii.
Outterm: An external or superficial thing; outward manner; superficial remark, etc.
Officiant: The officer who officiates or performs an office, as the burial office.
Operance: The act of operating or working; operation.
Ostracize: To exile by ostracism; to banish by a popular vote, as at Athens.
Offscouring: That which is scoured off; hence, refuse; rejected matter; that which is vile or despised.
off-line: Not connected; -- of computers or computer peripherals normally connected or intended to be connected to other computers by a communications line; as, we can't print the document because the printer is off-line.
ozonification: The act or process of producing, or of subjecting to the action of, ozone.
Ocher: A impure earthy ore of iron or a ferruginous clay, usually red (hematite) or yellow (limonite), -- used as a pigment in making paints, etc.  The name is also applied to clays of other colors.
Oblong: A rectangular figure longer than it is broad; hence, any figure longer than it is broad.
Osmose: The tendency in fluids to mix, or become equably diffused, when in contact.  Same as osmosis, which see.
Opposite: One who opposes; an opponent; an antagonist.
Obelisk: To mark or designate with an obelisk.
Oxymethylene: Formic aldehyde, regarded as a methylene derivative.
Orthogonally: Perpendicularly; at right angles; as, a curve cuts a set of curves orthogonally.
Orphrey: A band of rich embroidery, wholly or in part of gold, affixed to vestments, especially those of ecclesiastics.
Odorine: A pungent oily substance obtained by redistilling bone oil.
out-of-doors: Any location outside of any building, where the air is unconfined; the open air.
&Verbar;Opisthoglypha: A division of serpents which have some of the posterior maxillary teeth grooved for fangs.
obsessional: Persistently and abnormally preoccupied with some unreasonable idea.
one-upmanship: The attitude or practice of trying to keep one step ahead of a friend or competitor; vigorous competitiveness.
Olivaster: Of the color of the olive; tawny.
Overmorrow: The day after or following to-morrow.
Ordinarily: According to established rules or settled method; as a rule; commonly; usually; in most cases; as, a winter more than ordinarily severe.
omelet: A dish consisting of eggs beaten up with a little flour, etc., and cooked in a frying pan until just set into a semisolid consistency; it may be folded around e.g. ham or cheese or jelly; as, a plain omelet.  When additional ingredients are mixed in, the names of the ingredients may be mentioned in the name of the omelet; as, a ham and cheese omelet; a bacon and cheese omelet
&Verbar;Otozoum: An extinct genus of huge vertebrates, probably dinosaurs, known only from four-toed tracks in Triassic sandstones.
Osage: A member of the Osages, a tribe of North American Indians formerly living in western Missouri.
Osmometry: The study of osmosis by means of the osmometer.
Orby: Orblike; having the course of an orb; revolving.
Obviation: The act of obviating, or the state of being obviated.
Overwind: To wind too tightly, as a spring, or too far, as a hoisting rope on a drum.
Ocularly: By the eye, or by actual sight.
oxyacetic: Hydroxyacetic; designating an acid called also glycolic acid.
Ordinate: To appoint, to regulate; to harmonize.
Oxysulphide: A ternary compound of oxygen and sulphur.
Organotrophic: Relating to the creation, organization, and nutrition of living organs or parts.
Orthographer: One versed in orthography; one who spells words correctly.
Ogive: The arch or rib which crosses a Gothic vault diagonally.
Omentum: A free fold of the peritoneum, or one serving to connect viscera, support blood vessels, etc.; an epiploön.
Otiose: Being at leisure or ease; unemployed; indolent; idle.
Ostensibility: The quality or state of being ostensible.
-one: A termination indicating that the hydrocarbon to the name of which it is affixed belongs to the fourth series of hydrocarbons, or the third series of unsaturated hydrocarbons; as, nonone.
Oscillometer: An instrument for measuring the angle through which a ship rolls or pitches at sea.
Olympionic: An ode in honor of a victor in the Olympic games.
One-sided: Having one side only, or one side prominent.
Odious: Hateful; deserving or receiving hatred; as, an odious name, system, vice.
Observation post: a military outpost, usually at a height above the surrounding terrain, at or near the front line of a battle from which an observer may see the enemy's positions and direct artillery fire.
\u0152let: An eye, bud, or shoot, as of a plant; an oilet.
Outsee: To see beyond; to excel in certainty of seeing; to surpass in foresight.
oral surgery: Surgery performed within the mouth cavity, especially that performed around the gums and teeth as an expedient for the purpose of preservation or replacement of teeth.
Opacity: The state of being opaque; the quality of a body which renders it impervious to the rays of light; want of transparency; opaqueness.
open-ended: allowing for a spontaneous response; as, an open-ended question.  Contrasted to multiple-choice.
obsessed: having or showing excessive or compulsive concern; -- used with with.
Obitual: Of or pertaining to obits, or days when obits are celebrated; as, obitual days.
Oxalyl: A hydrocarbon radical (C2O2) regarded as a residue of oxalic acid and occurring in derivatives of it.
Outlinear: Of or pertaining to an outline; being in, or forming, an outline.
Oppositely: In a situation to face each other; in an opposite manner or direction; adversely.
Objicient: One who makes objection; an objector.
omnibus: Pertaining to or dealing with a variety of topics at one time; as, omnibus legislation; an omnibus budget bill.
Opponency: The act of opening an academical disputation; the proposition of objections to a tenet, as an exercise for a degree.
octothorp: A typographic symbol (#) having two vertical lines intersected by two horizontal lines.  It is also called the crosshatch, hash, numeral sign and number sign; in the U. S. it is commonly called the pound sign, especially to designate the symbol as used on digital telephone dials, but this can be confusing to Europeans who think of the pound sign as the symbol for the British pound.  It is commonly used as a symbol for the word number; as in #36 (meaning: number thirty-six).
Opinable: Capable of being opined or thought.
Overfeed: To feed to excess; to surfeit.
odd-job: varied and irregularly performed; -- of paid labor; as, he found only odd-job employment.
overdue: Due and more than due; delayed beyond the proper time of arrival, payment, return, etc.; as, an overdue vessel; an overdue note; a book overdue at the library; an overdue payment.
Outfrown: To frown down; to overbear by frowning.
overvaliant: Having or showing undue valor or boldness; as, they stepped with overvaliant airs.
off-road: designed for or used for or taking place on trails and beaches etc., instead of public roads; as, off-road vehicles; off-road sports such as snowmobiling.
Obstinacy: A fixedness in will, opinion, or resolution that can not be shaken at all, or only with great difficulty; firm and usually unreasonable adherence to an opinion, purpose, or system; unyielding disposition; stubborness; pertinacity; persistency; contumacy.
Oxyhydrogen: Of, pertaining to, or consisting of, a mixture of oxygen and hydrogen at over 5000° F.
open-chain: not cyclic; having no rings of atoms within the molecular structure; having an open chain structure.  Opposite of cyclic.
\u0152nocyan: The coloring matter of red wines.
Overstay: To stay beyond the time or the limits of; as, to overstay the appointed time; to overstay one's welcome.
Outtongue: To silence by talk, clamor, or noise.
old-maidish: Like an old maid; prim; precise; particular; overly fastidious.
Ointment: That which serves to anoint; any soft unctuous substance used for smearing or anointing; an unguent.
orb weaver: Any spider of the family Araneidae (called also Argiopidae) that spins a web with a pattern of lines spiraling outward from the center.  They have eight similar eyes.  The golden orb weaver, Mephila clavipes, is known for the remarkable dragline silk it produces for use as a frame for its web and as a line on which it can plummet down and nab prey.  This silk has a high tensile strength and is stronger than the toughest current synthetic polymer (Kevlar).
Opposable: Capable of being opposed or resisted.
oversexed: Having excessive sexual desire or appeal.
Odontoid: Having the form of a tooth; toothlike.
Onomatology: The science of names or of their classification.
overcount: A count{1} that is higher than the true number; an erroneously high number determined by counting incorrectly; the result of overcounting{2}.
overpowered: rendered powerless especially by an excessive amount or profusion of something.
Orthotone: Retaining the accent; not enclitic; -- said of certain indefinite pronouns and adverbs when used interrogatively, which, when not so used, are ordinarilly enclitic.
Obstetric: Of or pertaining to childbirth, midwifery, or the period around the time of the birth of children; as, the obstetric art.
orientating: aligning; positioning; setting into proper alignment.
Oligomyoid: Having few or imperfect syringeal muscles; -- said of some passerine birds (Oligomyodi).
offal: The rejected or waste parts of any process, especially the inedible parts of a butchered animal, such as the viscera.
Orectic: Of or pertaining to the desires; hence, impelling to gratification; appetitive.
Outfly: To surpass in flying; to fly beyond or faster than.
Oaken: Made or consisting of oaks or of the wood of oaks.
Outplay: To excel or defeat in a game; to play better than; as, to be outplayed in tennis or ball.
Osculatrix: A curve whose contact with a given curve, at a given point, is of a higher order (or involves the equality of a greater number of successive differential coefficients of the ordinates of the curves taken at that point) than that of any other curve of the same kind.
Oxonian: A student or graduate of Oxford University, in England.
Orchestian: Any species of amphipod crustacean of the genus Orchestia, or family Orchestidæ. See Beach flea, under Beach.
Outblush: To exceed in blushing; to surpass in rosy color.
onshore: coming from the sea toward the land; -- of winds and weather; as, an onshore gale.  Opposed to offshore.
\u0152iliad: A glance of the eye; an amorous look.
Outface: To face or look (one) out of countenance; to resist or bear down by bold looks or effrontery; to brave.
&Verbar;Orbitel\u00e6: A division of spiders, including those that make geometrical webs, as the garden spider, or Epeira.
Only: Save or except (that); -- an adversative used elliptically with or without that, and properly introducing a single fact or consideration.
Oppositionist: One who belongs to the opposition party.
Obduracy: The duality or state of being obdurate; invincible hardness of heart; obstinacy.
Oleography: Art or process of producing the pictures known as oleographs.
Oscillogram: An autographic record made by an oscillograph.
oilcan: A small can with a long spout used to apply oil to machinery, for purposes of lubrication.
Overpowering: Excelling in power; too powerful; irresistible.
Obstipation: The act of stopping up, as a passage.
Oleomargarine: A liquid oil made from animal fats (esp. beef fat) by separating the greater portion of the solid fat or stearin, by crystallization.  It is mainly a mixture of olein and palmitin with some little stearin.
Omdurman: A battle (1898) in which an Anglo-Egyptian army under Lord Kitchener defeated the Sudanese.
Oligochaeta: An order of Annelida which includes the earthworms and related species, including some small freshwater species.
outgoing: Going out; departing; leaving; as, the outgoing administration; an outgoing steamer.
operating: pr. p. of operate; as, the operating conditions of the oxidation pond.
Olibene: A colorless mobile liquid of a pleasant aromatic odor obtained by the distillation of olibanum, or frankincense, and regarded as a terpene; -- called also conimene.
Organoplastic: Having the property of producing the tissues or organs of animals and plants; as, the organoplastic cells.
obsecration: The act of obsecrating or imploring; as, the obsecrations of the Litany, being those clauses beginning with “By.”
outward-developing: Developing away from an axis, as in a flower cluster in which the oldest flowers are in the center, the youngest near the edge.
Oleoresin: A natural mixture of a terebinthinate oil and a resin.
Obturate: To stop or close, as an opening;
Ozonation: The act of treating with ozone; also, the act of converting into, or producing, ozone; ozonization.
Occasioner: One who, or that which, occasions, causes, or produces.
Orycterope: Same as Oryctere (the aardvark, Orycteropus afer).
&Verbar;Outr\u00e9: Out of the common course or limits; extravagant{2}; bizarre; outlandish{2}; as, an outré costume.
off-guard: not watching for possible danger; not alert; as, caught in an off-guard moment.
Oraculous: Oracular; of the nature of an oracle.
Otic: Of, pertaining to, or in the region of, the ear; auricular; auditory.
Orangery: A place for raising oranges; a plantation of orange trees.
Overdraft: The act of overdrawing; a draft in excess of the credit balance; also, the amount or sum overdrawn.
&Verbar;Oblatum: An oblate spheroid; a figure described by the revolution of an ellipse about its minor axis.  Cf. Oblongum.
Ocherous: Of or pertaining to ocher; containing or resembling ocher; as, ocherous matter; ocherous soil.
Oppilate: To crowd together; to fill with obstructions; to block up.
&Verbar;Obolus: A small silver coin of Athens, the sixth part of a drachma, about three cents in value.
odometer: An instrument attached to a vehicle or connected, as by a flexible cable, to the wheel of a vehicle, which measures the distance traversed.
Ochlocracy: A form of government by the multitude; a mobocracy; mob rule.
&Verbar;Olay: Palm leaves, prepared for being written upon with a style pointed with steel.
Oxycalcium: Of or pertaining to oxygen and calcium; as, the oxycalcium light. See Drummond light.
Obtruncation: The act of lopping or cutting off.
Osage orange: An ornamental tree of the genus Maclura (Maclura aurantiaca), closely allied to the mulberry (Morus); also, its fruit.  The tree was first found in the country of the Osage Indians, and bears a hard and inedible fruit of an orangelike appearance. See Bois d'arc.
Overslaugh: To hinder or stop, as by an overslaugh or an impediment; as, to overslaugh a bill in a legislative body; to overslaugh a military officer, that is, to hinder his promotion or employment.
Ossuary: A place where the bones of the dead are deposited; a charnel house.
Otaheite apple: The fruit of a Polynesian anacardiaceous tree (Spondias dulcis), also called vi-apple.  It is rather larger than an apple, and the rind has a flavor of turpentine, but the flesh is said to taste like pineapples.
Obdiplostemonous: Having twice as many stamens as petals, those of the outer set being opposite the petals; -- said of flowers.
Orthognathism: The quality or state of being orthognathous.
Obfuscation: The act of darkening or bewildering; the state of being darkened.
O\u00f6spore: A special kind of spore resulting from the fertilization of an oösphere by antherozoids.
onychophoran: Any of numerous velvety-skinned wormlike carnivorous animals common in tropical forests having characteristics of both arthropods and annelid worms; a member of the Onychophora, also called Malacopoda.  See  Malacopoda.
&Verbar;Olla-podrida: A favorite Spanish dish, consisting of a mixture of several kinds of meat chopped fine, and stewed with vegetables.
Orchestra: The space in a theater between the stage and the audience; -- originally appropriated by the Greeks to the chorus and its evolutions, afterward by the Romans to persons of distinction, and by the moderns to a band of instrumental musicians.  Now commonly called orchestra pit, to distinguish it from the section of the main floor occupied by spectators.
Octad: An atom or radical which has a valence of eight, or is octavalent.
Override: To ride over or across; to ride upon; to trample down.
Ormazd: The supreme deity, the embodiment of the principle of good, creator of the world, source of light, and guardian of mankind.  He is the opponent of Ahriman, the spirit of evil, both being sprung from Eternity, or, according to another version, Ahriman being the offspring of a moment of doubt on the part of Ormazd.  Ormazd is attended by angels and archangels.  He is represented as a bearded man inclosed in a winged circle, a conception probably derived from the Assyrian representations of Ashur.
Omphalopter: An optical glass that is convex on both sides.
Osiered: Covered or adorned with osiers; as, osiered banks.
Optic: Of, pertaining to, or using vision or sight; as, optical illusions.
Opening: The act or process of opening; a beginning; commencement; first appearance; as, the opening of a speech.
outfitting: the act of renovating and fitting out a ship.
&Verbar;Optimates: The nobility or aristocracy of ancient Rome, as opposed to the populares.
Onement: The state of being at one or reconciled.
Occasionalism: The system of occasional causes; -- a name given to certain theories of the Cartesian school of philosophers, as to the intervention of the First Cause, by which they account for the apparent reciprocal action of the soul and the body.
Oculonasal: Of or pertaining to the region of the eye and the nose; as, the oculonasal, or nasal, nerve, one of the branches of the ophthalmic.
Overbattle: Excessively fertile; bearing rank or noxious growths.
Open door: Open or free admission to all; hospitable welcome; free opportunity.
Oratrix: A woman plaintiff, or complainant, in equity pleading.
okay: to approve; as, the boss okayed my proposal.
&Verbar;Oscillaria: A genus of dark green, or purplish black, filamentous, fresh-water algæ, the threads of which have an automatic swaying or crawling motion. Called also Oscillatoria.
Oviparity: Generation by means of ova. See Generation.
Obtainment: The act or process of obtaining; attainment.
Oxychloride: A ternary compound of oxygen and chlorine; as, plumbic oxychloride.
Officialism: The state of being official; a system of official government; also, adherence to office routine; red-tapism.
oversewn: sewn together with overhand stitches (close vertical stitches that pass over and draw the two edges together.
once-over: a swift cursory examination or inspection; as, I gave him the once-over.
overnight: Ocurring or accomplished during one night; as, guaranteed overnight delivery of a package.
otterhound: A small hardy British hound having long pendulous ears and a thick coarse shaggy coat with an oily undercoat; bred in England for hunting otters.  Called also otter dog.
Ongoing: The act of going forward; progress; (pl.) affairs; business; current events.
outland: The regions of a country or territory remote from the main cities; the outlying provinces.
Onchorynchus: A genus of fishes including the sockeye salmon; chinook salmon; and coho salmon.
&Verbar;Ourebi: A small, graceful, and swift African antelope, allied to the klipspringer.
Olecranal: Of or pertaining to the olecranon.
Oscillograph: An apparatus for recording or indicating alternating-current wave forms or other electrical oscillations, especially of voltages or currents; it usually consists of a galvanometer with strong field, in which the mass of the moving part is very small and frequency of vibration very high.
outraged: deeply angered at something unjust or wrong; incensed; as, a look of outraged disbelief.
Orology: The science or description of mountains.
Obstruent: Anything that obstructs or closes a passage; esp., that which obstructs natural passages in the body; as, a medicine which acts as an obstruent.
Ominate: To presage; to foreshow; to foretoken.
Ophelic: Of, pertaining to, or designating, a substance (called ophelic acid) extracted from a plant (Ophelia) of the Gentian family as a bitter yellowish sirup, used in India as a febrifuge and tonic.
Ossein: The organic basis of bone tissue; the residue after removal of the mineral matters from bone by dilute acid; in embryonic tissue, the substance in which the mineral salts are deposited to form bone; bone collagen; -- called also ostein.  Chemically it is the same as collagen.
oxidization: The process of oxidizing; the addition of oxygen to a compound with a loss of electrons.  The process always occurs accompanied by reduction.
Opposition: The act of opposing; an attempt to check, restrain, or defeat; resistance.
Oarsman: One who uses, or is skilled in the use of, an oar; a rower.
Odocoileus: A genus of North American deer.
Obligable: Acknowledging, or complying with, obligation; trustworthy.
Oto-: A combining form denoting relation to the ear, or situation near the ear or in the ear.
Oriolus: The type genus of the Oriolidae.
Onoclea: A genus consisting of only species: the sensitive fern; in some classifications it is included in the Polypodiaceae.
Overly: Careless; negligent; inattentive; superfical; not thorough.
on-license: a license to sell liquor for consumption on the premises.
Orthoceratite: An orthoceras; also, any fossil shell allied to Orthoceras.
Organize: To furnish with organs; to give an organic structure to; to endow with capacity for the functions of life; as, an organized being; organized matter; -- in this sense used chiefly in the past participle.
Overdate: To date later than the true or proper period; to postdate.
Obumbrate: To shade; to darken; to cloud.
Ovolo: A round, convex molding. See Illust. of Column.
obligated: under a moral obligation to someone.
Onomatologist: One versed in the history of names.
Ochlocratic: Of or pertaining to ochlocracy; having the form or character of an ochlocracy; mobocratic.
Outscout: To overpower by disdain; to outface.
oppressed: having excessive or unfair burdens imposed.
Olfaction: The sense by which the impressions made on the olfactory organs by the odorous particles in the atmosphere are perceived.
Overbear: To bear fruit or offspring to excess; to be too prolific.
Overweather: To expose too long to the influence of the weather.
Overstand: To stand on the price or conditions of, so as to lose a sale; to lose by an extravagant price or hard conditions.
Oboe: One of the higher wind instruments in the modern orchestra, yet of great antiquity, having a penetrating pastoral quality of tone, somewhat like the clarinet in form, but more slender, and sounded by means of a double reed; a hautboy.
Optoc\u0153le: The cavity of one of the optic lobes of the brain in many animals.
Oppilation: The act of filling or crowding together; a stopping by redundant matter; obstruction, particularly in the lower intestines.
Outscouring: That which is scoured out or washed out.
Oblectation: The act of pleasing highly; the state of being greatly pleased; delight.
olefin: Olefiant gas, or ethylene. See Ethylene.
Overburden: The waste which overlies good stone in a quarry.
Offish: Shy or distant in manner; aloof; stand-offish.
Omber: A game at cards, borrowed from the Spaniards, and usually played by three persons.
Owlery: An abode or a haunt of owls.
Odium: Intense hatred or dislike; loathing; abhorrence.
Observation: The act or the faculty of observing or taking notice; the act of seeing, or of fixing the mind upon, anything.
O\u00f6phoric: Having the nature of, or belonging to, an oöphore.
Overtrading: The act or practice of buying goods beyond the means of payment; a glutting of the market.
Optometrist: One who is skilled in or practices optometry, especially one who examines the eyes for defects in vision and prescribes the proper lenses to correct any defects discovered.
outfitted: furnished with essential equipment for a particular occupation or undertaking occupation; as, a well-outfitted expedition to the South Pole.
Oculo-: A combining form from L. oculus the eye.
Octogild: A pecuniary compensation for an injury, of eight times the value of the thing.
Orthotropic: Having the longer axis vertical; -- said of erect stems.
orpine: A low plant with fleshy leaves (Sedum telephium), having clusters of purple flowers.  It is found on dry, sandy places, and on old walls, in England, and has become naturalized in America.  Called also stonecrop, and live-forever.
Oillet: A small opening or loophole, sometimes circular, used in mediæval fortifications.
Ogreism: The character or manners of an ogre.
Outgaze: To gaze beyond; to exceed in sharpness or persistence of seeing or of looking; hence, to stare out of countenance.
Ovaliform: Having the form of an egg; having a figure such that any section in the direction of the shorter diameter will be circular, and any in the direction of the longer diameter will be oval.
Orthopedist: One who prevents, cures, or remedies deformities, esp. in children.
Oblongness: State or quality of being oblong.
Orchid: Any plant of the order Orchidaceæ.  See Orchidaceous.
Oxytoluene: One of three hydroxy derivatives of toluene, called the cresols. See Cresol.
Overbulk: To oppress by bulk; to overtower.
Opeidoscope: An instrument, consisting of a tube having one end open and the other end covered with a thin flexible membrance to the center of which is attached a small mirror.  It is used for exhibiting upon a screen, by means of rays reflected from the mirror, the vibratory motions caused by sounds produced at the open end of the tube, as by speaking or singing into it.
Opprobrious: Expressive of opprobrium; attaching disgrace; reproachful; scurrilous; as, opprobrious language.
Oxindol: A white crystalline nitrogenous substance (C8H7NO) of the indol group, obtained by the reduction of dioxindol.  It is a so-called lactam compound.
Omosternal: Of or pertaining to the omosternum.
Offskip: That part of a landscape which recedes from the spectator into the distance.
Olivine: A common name of the yellowish green mineral chrysolite, esp. the variety found in eruptive rocks.  It is a silicate of magnesium and iron ((Mg,Fe)SiO4).
optical fiber: A thin fiber of very pure glass used to carry signals transmitted by means of light.  It has much greater information-carrying capacity than a copper wire, and in the 1990's became a dominant means of transmitting telephone communications over long distances.
Orderliness: The state or quality of being orderly.
Obversion: The act of turning toward or downward.
Oreodon: A genus of extinct herbivorous mammals, abundant in the Tertiary formation of the Rocky Mountains.  It is more or less related to the camel, hog, and deer.
&Verbar;Oculinacea: A suborder of corals including many reef-building species, having round, starlike calicles.
Otocrane: The cavity in the skull in which the parts of the internal ear are lodged.
Obturator: Serving as an obturator; closing an opening; pertaining to, or in the region of, the obturator foramen; as, the obturator nerve.
Olympus: A mountain in Northeastern Greece; -- it was believed by ancient Greeks to be the dwelling place of the gods.
Order: To give orders; to issue commands.
Orgue: Any one of a number of long, thick pieces of timber, pointed and shod with iron, and suspended, each by a separate rope, over a gateway, to be let down in case of attack.
orthopedics: The art or practice of correcting disorders or deformities of the spine and joints, or, by extension, any deformities of the human body.
Octopede: An animal having eight feet, as a spider.
on-site: Taking place or located at the indicated site; as, on-site inspection.  Opposed to off-site.
Overexertion: Excessive exertion; as, he strained his back from overexertion.
Operculiform: Having the form of a lid or cover.
Oratress: A woman who makes public addresses.
Outwing: To surpass, exceed, or outstrip in flying.
oxtongue: A widespread European weed (Picris echioides formerly Helminthia echioides) with spiny tongue-shaped leaves and yellow flowers.  The name is applied to several plants, from the shape and roughness of their leaves; as, Anchusa officinalis, a kind of bugloss, and Helminthia echioides, both European herbs.  It has been naturalized in the U. S.
&Verbar;Olpe: Originally, a leather flask or vessel for oils or liquids; afterward, an earthenware vase or pitcher without a spout.
Opinicus: An imaginary animal borne as a charge, having wings, an eagle's head, and a short tail; -- sometimes represented without wings.
Orcus: The god of the underworld; counterpart of Greek Pluto.
Occipito-: A combining form denoting relation to the occiput, or situation near the occiput; as, occipito-axial; occipito-mastoid.
Octateuch: A collection of eight books; especially, the first eight books of the Old Testament.
O\u00f6lite: A variety of limestone, consisting of small round grains, resembling the roe of a fish.  It sometimes constitutes extensive beds, as in the European Jurassic. See the Chart of Geology.
Overpicture: To surpass nature in the picture or representation of.
Orcadian: Of or pertaining to the Orkney Islands.
Omniscience: The quality or state of being omniscient; the quality of knowing everything; -- an attribute peculiar to God.
Owe: To possess; to have, as the rightful owner; to own.
Ophiology: That part of natural history which treats of the ophidians, or serpents.
Oolong: A fragrant variety of black tea having somewhat the flavor of green tea.
Oilman: One who deals in oils; formerly, one who dealt in oils and pickles.
Oversow: To sow where something has already been sown.
Outtalk: To overpower by talking; to exceed in talking; to talk down.
Oliver: A small tilt hammer, worked by the foot.
Omniety: That which is all-pervading or all-comprehensive; hence, the Deity.
Orbitonasal: Of or pertaining to the orbit and the nose; as, the orbitonasal, or ophthalmic, nerve.
&Verbar;Osteoporosis: An absorption of bone so that the bone tissue becomes unusually porous.  It occurs especially in elderly men and postmenopausal women, and predisposes the elderly to fractures of the bones.
Ostmen: East men; Danish settlers in Ireland, formerly so called.
Outparish: A parish lying without the walls of, or in a remote part of, a town.
Overlayer: One who overlays; that with which anything is overlaid.
Olived: Decorated or furnished with olive trees.
odograph: A machine for registering the distance traversed by a vehicle or pedestrain.
Outtell: To surpass in telling, counting, or reckoning.
Otididae: A family of birds related to the cranes, most of which are large and ground-running, and comprising the bustards.
Onion: A liliaceous plant of the genus Allium (Allium cepa), having a strong-flavored bulb and long hollow leaves; also, its bulbous root, much used as an article of food.  The name is often extended to other species of the genus.
Orthoxylene: That variety of xylene (C6H4(CH3)2) in which the two methyl groups are in the ortho position; a colorless, liquid, combustible hydrocarbon resembling benzene.
Ortygan: One of several species of East Indian birds of the genera Ortygis and Hemipodius.  They resemble quails, but lack the hind toe. See Turnix.
Overture: To make an overture to; as, to overture a religious body on some subject.
Ozonize: To convert into ozone, as oxygen.
Oreodont: Resembling, or allied to, the genus Oreodon.
&Verbar;Octandria: A Linnæan class of plants, in which the flowers have eight stamens not united to one another or to the pistil.
Outwind: To extricate by winding; to unloose.
Ordnance: Heavy weapons of warfare; cannon, or great guns, mortars, and howitzers; artillery; sometimes, a general term for all weapons, ammunitiion, and appliances used in war.
Overmultiply: To multiply or increase too much; to repeat too often.
Otto engine: An engine using the Otto cycle.
Officialty: The charge, office, court, or jurisdiction of an official.
Ophism: Doctrines and rites of the Ophites.
Outrank: To exceed in rank; hence, to take precedence of.
Orbit: The path described by a heavenly body in its periodical revolution around another body; as, the orbit of Jupiter, of the earth, of the moon.
&Verbar;On dit: They say, or it is said.
&Verbar;ojo: A spring, surrounded by rushes or rank grass; an oasis.
Omnium-gatherum: A miscellaneous collection of things or persons; a confused mixture; a medley; a hodgepodge.
Overlordship: Lordship or supremacy of a person or a people over others.
off-key: Deviating from the proper pitch; -- of a musical note or series of notes; as, an off-key note; to sing off-key.
Oxychloric: Of, pertaining to, or designating in general, certain compounds containing oxygen and chlorine.
Obvolute: Overlapping; contorted; convolute; -- applied primarily, in botany, to two opposite leaves, each of which has one edge overlapping the nearest edge of the other, and secondarily to a circle of several leaves or petals which thus overlap.
Overchange: Too much or too frequent change; fickleness.
Opitulation: The act of helping or aiding; help.
Orthodox: Sound in opinion or doctrine, especially in religious doctrine; hence, holding the Christian faith; believing the doctrines taught in the Scriptures; -- opposed to heretical and heterodox; as, an orthodox Christian.
outhouse: A small house or building at a little distance from the main house; an outbuilding.
Ornithorhynchidae: The natural family of monotremes including the platypus (duckbill) (Ornithorhyncus anatinus).
overdrive: A gearing device which causes the drive shaft of an automobile or other machine to rotate at a speed greater than that of the engine crankshaft.
Overflourish: To make excessive display or flourish of.
officialize: to render official; as, we officialized our relationship.
Observant: One who observes forms and rules.
Ovary: That part of the pistil which contains the seed, and in most flowering plants develops into the fruit. See Illust. of Flower.
Old-maidism: The condition or characteristics of an old maid.
Occupancy: The act of taking or holding possession, especially of real property or rental property; possession; occupation.
Ophthalmite: An eyestalk; the organ which bears the compound eyes of decapod Crustacea.
Oakum: The material obtained by untwisting and picking into loose fiber old hemp ropes; -- used for calking the seams of ships, stopping leaks, etc.
Overaffect: To affect or care for unduly.
Old Line State: Maryland; a nickname, alluding to the fact that its northern boundary is Mason and Dixon's line.
Oxymuriate: A salt of the supposed oxymuriatic acid; a chloride.
Overalls: A kind of loose trousers worn over others to protect them from soiling.
Open-eyed: With eyes widely open; alert to possible danger; watchful; vigilant.
Overbrim: To flow over the brim; to be so full as to overflow.
Overword: To say in too many words; to express verbosely.
Opposability: The condition or quality of being opposable.
Overworn: Worn out or subdued by toil; worn out so as to be trite.
Octonaphthene: A colorless liquid hydrocarbon of the octylene series, occurring in Caucasian petroleum.
Odds: Difference in favor of one and against another; excess of one of two things or numbers over the other; inequality; advantage; superiority; hence, excess of chances; probability.  The odds are often expressed by a ratio; as, the odds are three to one that he will win, i. e. he will win three times out of four
Omit: To let go; to leave unmentioned; not to insert or name; to drop.
Overslip: To slip or slide over; to pass easily or carelessly beyond; to omit; to neglect; as, to overslip time or opportunity.
Overwork: Work in excess of the usual or stipulated time or quantity; extra work; also, excessive labor.
Onerary: Fitted for, or carrying, a burden.
overutilization: exploitation to the point of diminishing returns.
&Verbar;Ovipara: An artificial division of vertebrates, including those that lay eggs; -- opposed to Vivipara.
Optography: The production of an optogram on the retina by the photochemical action of light on the visual purple; the fixation of an image in the eye.  The object so photographed shows white on a purple or red background.  See Visual purple, under Visual.
Obcordate: Heart-shaped, with the attachment at the pointed end; inversely cordate; as, an obcordate petal or leaf.
&Verbar;O\u00f6phoridium: The macrosporangium or case for the larger kind of spores in heterosporous flowerless plants.
Outcry: A vehement or loud cry; a cry of distress, alarm, opposition, or detestation; clamor.
Oppositifolious: Placed at the same node with a leaf, but separated from it by the whole diameter of the stem; as, an oppositifolious peduncle.
Orrery: An apparatus which illustrates, by the revolution of balls moved by wheelwork, the relative size, periodic motions, positions, orbits, etc., of bodies in the solar system.
Ore: Honor; grace; favor; mercy; clemency; happy augury.
Orsellic: Pertaining to, or designating, an acid found in certain lichens, and called also lecanoric acid.
Overstock: To fill too full; to supply in excess; as, to overstock a market with goods, or a farm with cattle.
objective lens: An object glass.  See under Object, n.
Overman: One in authority over others; a chief; usually, an overseer or boss.
overhanded: performed with the arm moving above the shoulder; overhand{2}; -- of methods of throwing, especially in baseball.  Contrasted with underhand and sidearm.
Ob-: A prefix signifying to, toward, before, against, reversely, etc.; also, as a simple intensive; as in oblige, to bind to; obstacle, something standing before; object, lit., to throw against; obovate, reversely, or oppositely, ovate. Ob- is commonly assimilated before c, f, g, and p, to oc-, of-, og-, and op-.
Obverse: The face of a coin which has the principal image or inscription upon it; -- the other side being the reverse.
oil-bearing: containing oils; -- of geological formations; as, oil-bearing shale.
Overbreed: To breed to excess; as, the bulls were so huge and overbred no matador wanted to fight them.
Overmount: To mount over; to go higher than; to rise above.
Oxalan: A complex nitrogenous substance C3N3H5O3 obtained from alloxan (or when urea is fused with ethyl oxamate), as a stable white crystalline powder; -- called also oxaluramide.
Overfront: To confront; to oppose; to withstand.
Omental: Of or pertaining to an omentum or the omenta.
Oroide: An alloy, chiefly of copper and zinc or tin, resembling gold in color and brilliancy.
Outreason: To excel or surpass in reasoning; to reason better than.
Orator: A public speaker; one who delivers an oration; especially, one distinguished for his skill and power as a public speaker; one who is eloquent.
Opisthodome: A back chamber; especially, that part of the naos, or cella, farthest from the main entrance, sometimes having an entrance of its own, and often used as a treasury.
Obi: A sash, esp. the long belt-like broad sash of soft material worn by women aound the waist when wearing a traditional kimono, and usually having a large bow at the back.
outwardness: concern with outward things or material objects (esp the body and its appearance) as opposed to the mind or the spirit or ideal concepts; as, hearty showmanship and all-around outwardness.
Obliterate: Scarcely distinct; -- applied to the markings of insects.
Obtend: To oppose; to hold out in opposition.
Oneness: The state of being one; singleness in number; individuality; unity.
&Verbar;Osteosarcoma: A tumor having the structure of a sarcoma in which there is a deposit of bone; sarcoma connected with bone.
Ozonizer: An apparatus or agent for the production or application of ozone.
Organicism: The doctrine of the localization of disease, or which refers it always to a material lesion of an organ.
-ory: An adjective suffix meaning of or pertaining to, serving for; as in auditory, pertaining to or serving for hearing; prohibitory, amendatory, etc.
Observance: The act or practice of observing or noticing with attention; a heeding or keeping with care; performance; -- usually with a sense of strictness and fidelity; as, the observance of the Sabbath is general; the strict observance of duties.
&Verbar;Oliva: A genus of polished marine gastropod shells, chiefly tropical, and often beautifully colored.
&Verbar;Osteocomma: A metamere of the vertebrate skeleton; an osteomere; a vertebra.
Oleandrin: One of several cardiac glycosides (C32H48O9) found in oleander (Nerium oleander).
Overrake: To rake over, or sweep across, from end to end, as waves that break over a vessel anchored with head to the sea.
Outstrip: To go faster than; to outrun; to advance beyond; to leave behind.
outward-moving: moving or directed away from center, especially when spinning or traveling in a curve.
&Verbar;Oryza: A genus of grasses including the rice plant; rice.
Overvalue: To value excessively; to rate at too high a price.
&Verbar;Odelsthing: The lower house of the Norwegian Storthing. See Legislature.
Opossum: Any American marsupial of the genera Didelphys and Chironectes; called also possum.  The common species of the United States is Didelphys Virginiana.
Obligor: The person who binds himself, or gives his bond to another.
Overskirt: An upper skirt, shorter than the dress, and usually draped.
Outgush: To gush out; to flow forth.
Ornitho-: A combining form fr. Gr. 'o`rnis, 'o`rniqos, a bird.
Outslide: To slide outward, onward, or forward; to advance by sliding.
Orthodoxly: In an orthodox manner; with soundness of faith.
Orillon: A semicircular projection made at the shoulder of a bastion for the purpose of covering the retired flank, -- found in old fortresses.
Outjet: That which jets out or projects from anything.
Orpin: A yellow pigment of various degrees of intensity, approaching also to red.
Overbalance: Excess of weight or value; something more than an equivalent; as, an overbalance of exports.
Originalness: The quality of being original; originality.
Orthotomy: The property of cutting at right angles.
ozocerite: A waxlike mineral resin; -- sometimes called native paraffin, and mineral wax.
Orderer: One who puts in order, arranges, methodizes, or regulates.
Outgo: That which goes out, or is paid out; outlay; expenditure; -- the opposite of income; as, when one's outgo exceeds one's income, distress follows quickly.
Orbitosphenoidal: Of or pertaining to the orbitosphenoid bone; orbitosphenoid.
Openness: The quality or state of being open.
oil rig: A structure and associated machinery used in drilling for oil or gas; it is usually in the form of a tower.  Called also drilling rig.
ossicular: Of or pertaining to an ossicle.
Onagraceous: Pertaining to, or resembling, a natural order of plants (Onagraceæ or Onagrarieæ), which includes the fuchsia, the willow-herb (Epilobium), and the evening primrose (Œnothera).
Outname: To exceed in naming or describing.
Outsider: One not belonging to the concern, institution, party, etc., spoken of; one disconnected in interest or feeling.
Objection: The act of objecting; as, to prevent agreement, or action, by objection.
Oligocene: Of, pertaining to, or designating, certain strata which occupy an intermediate position between the Eocene and Miocene periods.
Oblatration: The act of oblatrating; a barking or snarling.
old fashioned: A cocktail consisting of whiskey, bitters, and sugar, garnished with with fruit slices and often a cherry.
Opine: To have an opinion; to judge; to think; to suppose.
Oriflamb: The ancient royal standard of France.
Outstare: To excel or overcome in staring; to face down.
Opisthopulmonate: Having the pulmonary sac situated posteriorly; -- said of certain air-breathing Mollusca.
&Verbar;Organon: An organ or instrument; hence, a method by which philosophical or scientific investigation may be conducted; -- a term adopted from the Aristotelian writers by Lord Bacon, as the title (“Novum Organon”) of part of his treatise on philosophical method.
Oilseed: Seed from which oil is expressed, as the castor bean; also, the plant yielding such seed. See Castor bean.
orientated: Adjusted or aligned to surroundings or circumstances; sometimes used in combination; as, to get oriented on one's first day at a new job.
Osmund: A fern of the genus Osmunda, or flowering fern.  The most remarkable species is the osmund royal, or royal fern (Osmunda regalis), which grows in wet or boggy places, and has large bipinnate fronds, often with a panicle of capsules at the top.  The rootstock contains much starch, and has been used in stiffening linen.
Optimistic: Of or pertaining to optimism; tending, or conforming, to the opinion that all events are ordered for the best.
Ophthalmoscopy: A branch of physiognomy which deduces the knowledge of a person's temper and character from the appearance of the eyes.
overcrow: To crow, exult, or boast, over; to overpower.
overcrop: to exhaust (arable land) by excessive cultivation.
Orthographist: One who spells words correctly; an orthographer.
Obstringe: To constrain; to put under obligation.
Olfersia: genus consisting of one species; in some classification systems it is included in the genus Polyboatrya.
Outfitter: One who furnishes outfits for a voyage, a journey, or a business.
operationalism: the doctrine that the meaning of a proposition consists of the operations involved in defining, proving, or applying it.
Ophthalmoscope: An instrument for viewing the interior of the eye, particularly the retina.  Light is thrown into the eye by a mirror (usually concave) and the interior is then examined with or without the aid of a lens.
Orphean: Of or pertaining to Orpheus, the mythic poet and musician; as, Orphean strains.
Overdo: To labor too hard; to do too much.
Overleaven: To leaven too much; hence, to change excessively; to spoil.
Outlying: Lying or being at a distance from the central part, or the main body; being on, or beyond, the frontier; exterior; remote; detached.
&Verbar;Onager: A military engine acting like a sling, which threw stones from a bag or wooden bucket, and was operated by machinery.
Occidentals: Western Christians of the Latin rite.  See Orientals.
O\u00f6sperm: The ovum, after fusion with the spermatozoön in impregnation.
Operative: A skilled worker; an artisan; esp., one who operates a machine in a mill or manufactory.
one-year: completing its life cycle within a year.
Orphic: Pertaining to Orpheus; Orphean; as, Orphic hymns.
&Verbar;Osteosclerosis: Abnormal hardness and density of bone.
OAS: The Organization of American States an international association of countries in the Western hemisphere.  It was created in 1948 to promote military and economic and social and cultural cooperation.
Orthostichy: A longitudinal rank, or row, of leaves along a stem.
Obuncous: Hooked or crooked in an extreme degree.
Obole: A weight of twelve grains; or, according to some, of ten grains, or half a scruple.
Orichalch: A metallic substance, resembling gold in color, but inferior in value; a mixed metal of the ancients, resembling brass; -- called also aurichalcum, orichalcum, etc.
&Verbar;Octroi: A privilege granted by the sovereign authority, as the exclusive right of trade granted to a guild or society; a concession.
Omnipotence: The state of being omnipotent; almighty power; hence, one who is omnipotent; the Deity.
Orphanotrophism: The care and support of orphans.
Orsedew: Leaf metal of bronze; Dutch metal. See under Dutch.
officialese: the formal and often obscure style of writing characteristic of some government officials; bureaucratese; -- it is characterized by euphemisms, circumlocutions, vague abstractions, and circumlocutions.
Obscurer: One who, or that which, obscures.
Ordination: The act of ordaining, appointing, or setting apart; the state of being ordained, appointed, etc.
Ophiurioid: Of or pertaining to the Ophiurioidea.
Outmarch: To surpass in marching; to march faster than, or so as to leave behind.
Obconic: Conical, but having the apex downward; inversely conical.
Oxime: One of a series of isonitroso derivatives obtained by the action of hydroxylamine on aldehydes or ketones.
Overrun: To run, pass, spread, or flow over or by something; to be beyond, or in excess.
On: Forward, in progression; onward; -- usually with a verb of motion; as, move on; go on; the beat goes on.
Orchidaceous: Pertaining to, or resembling, a natural order (Orchidaceæ) of endogenous plants of which the genus Orchis is the type.  They are mostly perennial herbs having the stamens and pistils united in a single column, and normally three petals and three sepals, all adherent to the ovary.  The flowers are curiously shaped, often resembling insects, the odd or lower petal (called the lip) being unlike the others, and sometimes of a strange and unexpected appearance.  About one hundred species occur in the United States, but several thousand in the tropics.
Oh: An exclamation expressing various emotions, according to the tone and manner, especially surprise, pain, sorrow, anxiety, or a wish. See the Note under O.
Of: In a general sense, from, or out from; proceeding from; belonging to; relating to; concerning; -- used in a variety of applications; as:
Opal: A mineral consisting, like quartz, of silica, but inferior to quartz in hardness and specific gravity.
Od: An alleged force or natural power, supposed, by Reichenbach and others, to produce the phenomena of mesmerism, and to be developed by various agencies, as by magnets, heat, light, chemical or vital action, etc.; -- called also odyle or the odylic force.
Opah: A large oceanic fish (Lampris guttatus), inhabiting the Atlantic Ocean.  It is remarkable for its brilliant colors, which are red, green, and blue, with tints of purple and gold, covered with round silvery spots.  Called also king of the herrings.
Ox: The male of bovine quadrupeds, especially the domestic animal when castrated and grown to its full size, or nearly so. The word is also applied, as a general name, to any species of bovine animals, male and female.
Offshoot: That which shoots off or separates from a main stem, channel, family, race, etc.; as, the offshoots of a tree.
Os: The chemical symbol for the element osmium.
Or: Yellow or gold color, -- represented in drawing or engraving by small dots.
outright: Immediately; without delay; at once; as, he was killed outright.
Ophite: A mamber of a Gnostic serpent-worshiping sect of the second century.
ogdoad: A thing made up of eight parts.
Owelty: Equality; -- sometimes written ovelty and ovealty.
Orthodromy: The act or art of sailing on a great circle.
oncoming: the beginning or early stages; the onset.
ozena: A discharge of fetid matter from the nostril, particularly if associated with ulceration of the soft parts and disease of the bones of the nose.
&Verbar;Opisthion: The middle of the posterior, or dorsal, margin of the great foramen of the skull.
outpope the Pope: To try to act as a more authentic member of a group than one who is a genuine member of the group; -- not necessarily in reference to religious matters;  compare to be more Catholic than the Pope.
Obloquy: Censorious speech; defamatory language; language that casts contempt on men or their actions; blame; reprehension.
obligee: The person to whom another is bound, or the person to whom a bond is given.
Outlimb: An extreme member or part of a thing; a limb.
one-way: Legally permitting movement or travel in one direction only; -- of paths, especially roads; as, one-way streets.
Ovular: Relating or belonging to an ovule; as, an ovular growth.
Overgrow: To grow beyond the fit or natural size; to grow too large; as, a huge, overgrown ox.
obliger: One who, or that which, obliges.
ozone: A colorless gaseous substance (O3) obtained (as by the silent discharge of electricity in oxygen) as an allotropic form of oxygen, containing three atoms in the molecule.  It is a strong oxidizer, and probably exists in the air, though by the ordinary tests it is liable to be confused with certain other substances, as hydrogen dioxide, or certain oxides of nitrogen.  It derives its name from its peculiar odor, which resembles that of weak chlorine.
onymous: bearing a name; as, articles in magazines are usually onymous.  Opposite of anonymous.
Oleandraceae: One of a number of families into which Polypodiaceae has been subdivided in some classification systems.
Overproportion: To make of too great proportion.
Occurrent: One who meets; hence, an adversary.
Odic: Of or pertaining to od. See Od.
osmium: A rare metallic element of the platinum group with atomic number 76.  It is found native as an alloy in platinum ore, and in iridosmine.  It is a hard, infusible, bluish or grayish white metal, and the heaviest substance known.  Its tetroxide is used in histological experiments to stain tissues. Symbol Os.  Atomic weight 190.2.  Specific gravity 22.477.
Odin: The supreme deity of the Scandinavians; -- the same as Woden, of the German tribes.
Overwax: To wax or grow too rapidly or too much.
O: An exclamation used in calling or directly addressing a person or personified object; also, as an emotional or impassioned exclamation expressing pain, grief, surprise, desire, fear, etc.
Oleandrine: One of several alkaloids found in the leaves of the oleander (Nerium oleander).
onside: Not offside; being within the prescribed area of play.
Oratorical: Of or pertaining to an orator or to oratory; characterized by oratory; rhetorical; becoming to an orator; as, an oratorical triumph; an oratorical essay.
Obduction: The act of drawing or laying over, as a covering.
Outwall: The exterior wall; the outside surface, or appearance.
Overfull: Too full; filled to overflowing; excessively full; surfeited.
Operate: To produce, as an effect; to cause.
offside: Illegally beyond a prescribed line or area or ahead of the ball or puck; -- in sports such as football or hockey; as, the touchdown was nullified because the left tackle was offside.
Ogham: A particular kind of writing practiced by the ancient Irish, and found in inscriptions on stones, metals, etc.
Obtrusion: The act of obtruding; a thrusting upon others by force or unsolicited; as, the obtrusion of crude opinions on the world.
Orography: That branch of science which treats of mountains and mountain systems; orology; as, the orography of Western Europe.
Out-patient: A patient who is outside a hospital, but receives medical aid from it.
on-the-scene: Being or occurring at the place or time in question; as, an on-the-scene newscast.
Ortalidian: Any one of numerous small two-winged flies of the family Ortalidæ.  The larvæ of many of these flies live in fruit; those of others produce galls on various plants.
Octa-: A prefix meaning eight. See Octo-.
on-duty: performing or available for duties; as, her on-duty hours were 11p.m. to 7 a.m..  Opposite of off-duty.
Outbrave: To excel in bravery or in insolence; to defy with superior courage or audacity.
oldwife: The local name of various fishes, as the European black sea bream (Cantharus lineatus), the American alewife, etc.
Organling: A large kind of sea fish; the orgeis.
Outwalk: To excel in walking; to leave behind in walking.
oxidized: combined with or having undergone a chemical reaction with oxygen; as, the oxidized form of iodine.
Oceanid: A daughter of the Titans Oceanus and Tethys.
Oppressive: Unreasonably burdensome; unjustly severe, rigorous, or harsh; as, oppressive taxes; oppressive exactions of service; an oppressive game law.
Orthoclase: Common or potash feldspar crystallizing in the monoclinic system and having two cleavages at right angles to each other. See Feldspar.
Octahedron: A solid bounded by eight faces.  The regular octahedron is contained by eight equal equilateral triangles.
Oop: To bind with a thread or cord; to join; to unite.
Oryzopsis: A genus of grasses incluiding rice grass.
Obit: Death; decease; the date of one's death.
&Verbar;Orthoceras: An extinct genus of Paleozoic Cephalopoda, having a long, straight, conical shell.  The interior is divided into numerous chambers by transverse septa.
Orthodoxical: Pertaining to, or evincing, orthodoxy; orthodox.
Occlusion: The act of occluding, or the state of being occluded.
Oughtness: The state of being as a thing ought to be; rightness.
Ordinator: One who ordains or establishes; a director.
Overjump: To jump over; hence, to omit; to ignore.
Opinionator: An opinionated person; one given to conjecture.
Odist: A writer of an ode or odes.
Orientate: To move or turn toward the east; to veer from the north or south toward the east.
Occultism: A certain Oriental system of theosophy.
Office: To perform, as the duties of an office; to discharge.
Officiate: To discharge, perform, or supply, as an official duty or function.
Odontostomatous: Having toothlike mandibles; -- applied to certain insects.
Overagitate: To agitate or discuss beyond what is expedient.
Oyez: Hear; attend; -- a term used by criers of courts to secure silence before making a proclamation.  It is repeated three times.
Oxygon: A triangle having three acute angles.
Obedient: Subject in will or act to authority; willing to obey; submissive to restraint, control, or command.
Oyer: A hearing or an inspection, as of a deed, bond, etc., as when a defendant in court prays oyer of a writing.
Onomatopoetic: Of or pertaining to onomatopœia; characterized by onomatopœia; imitative; as, an onomatopoetic writer or word.
Odylic: Of or pertaining to odyle; odic; as, odylic force.
ordered: having or evincing a systematic arrangement; especially, having elements succeeding in order according to rule; as, an ordered sequence; an ordered pair.  Opposite of disordered or unordered.
oddity: The quality or state of being odd; singularity; queerness; peculiarity; as, oddity of dress, manners, and the like.
Overconfidence: Excessive confidence; too great reliance or trust.
Overvote: To outvote; to outnumber in votes given.
Outside: On or to the outside (of); without; on the exterior; as, to ride outside the coach; he stayed outside.
Overhead: Aloft; above; in or attached to the ceiling or roof; in the story or upon the floor above; in the zenith.
organizational: of or pertaining to organization; as, organizational structure.
Occident: The part of the horizon where the sun last appears in the evening; that part of the earth towards the sunset; the west; -- opposed to orient.  Specifically, in former times, Europe as opposed to Asia; now, also, the Western hemisphere.
Organicalness: The quality or state of being organic.
Ossivorous: Feeding on bones; eating bones; as, ossivorous quadrupeds.
Overfatigue: To fatigue to excess; to tire out.
Organdie: A kind of transparent light but stiff muslin.
Ophiuran: Of or pertaining to the Ophiurioidea.
&Verbar;Oubliette: A dungeon with an opening only at the top, found in some old castles and other strongholds, into which persons condemned to perpetual imprisonment, or to perish secretly, were thrust, or lured to fall.
Omicron: Lit., the little, or short, O, o; the fifteenth letter of the Greek alphabet.
&Verbar;Orgyia: A genus of bombycid moths whose caterpillars (esp. those of Orgyia leucostigma) are often very injurious to fruit trees and shade trees.  The female is wingless.  Called also vaporer moth.
Octagon: A plane figure of eight sides and eight angles.
Ozonoscope: An apparatus employed to indicate the presence, or the amount, of ozone.
Opera: A drama, either tragic or comic, of which music forms an essential part; a drama wholly or mostly sung, consisting of recitative, arias, choruses, duets, trios, etc., with orchestral accompaniment, preludes, and interludes, together with appropriate costumes, scenery, and action; a lyric drama.
onionskin: A kind of thin but strong translucent paper with a glossy finish.
Oleaginous: Having the nature or qualities of oil; oily; unctuous.
Omphalo-: A combining form indicating connection with, or relation to, the umbilicus, or navel.
Outpension: A public pension granted to one not required to live in a charitable institution.
Oxyphenic: Pertaining to, or designating, the phenol formerly called oxyphenic acid, and now oxyphenol and pyrocatechin. See Pyrocatechin.
Observation car: A railway passenger car made so as to facilitate seeing the scenery en route; a car open, or with glass sides, or with a kind of open balcony at the rear.
\u0152nanthyl: A hydrocarbon radical formerly supposed to exist in œnanthic acid, now known to be identical with heptyl.
Ovoviviparous: Oviparous, but hatching the egg while it is within the body, as some fishes and reptiles.
Organic: Of or pertaining to an organ or its functions, or to objects composed of organs; consisting of organs, or containing them; as, the organic structure of animals and plants; exhibiting characters peculiar to living organisms; as, organic bodies, organic life, organic remains.  Cf. Inorganic.
oceangoing: capable of crossing an ocean;  used on the high seas; -- used mostly of ships; as, oceangoing vessels.
Outfall: The mouth of a river; the lower end of a water course; the open end of a drain, culvert, etc., where the discharge occurs.
Output: The amount or quantity of a material or product that is produced by a mine, factory, or any system for production of commercial goods, such as the amount of coal or ore put out from one or more mines, or the quantity of material produced by, or turned out from, one or more furnaces or mills, in a given time; production.
Ovate-subulate: Having an ovate form, but with a subulate tip or extremity.
Oblique-angled: Having oblique angles; as, an oblique-angled triangle.
Ochroleucous: Yellowish white; having a faint tint of dingy yellow.
Octachord: An instrument of eight strings; a system of eight tones.
Origenism: The opinions of Origen of Alexandria, who lived in the 3d century, one of the most learned of the Greek Fathers.  Prominent in his teaching was the doctrine that all created beings, including Satan, will ultimately be saved.
Origenist: A follower of Origen of Alexandria.
Omander wood: The wood of Diospyros ebenaster, a kind of ebony found in Ceylon.
Oxyhydrogen light: A light produced by the incandescence of some substances, esp. lime, in the oxyhydrogen flame.  Coal gas (producing the oxygas light), or the vapor of ether (oxyether light) or methylated spirit (oxyspirit light), may be substituted for hydrogen.
onion dome: A dome with a pointed top, its width often extending beyond the width of the tower it covers; -- a style of architecture characteristic of Russian Orthodox churches.
Ochotonidae: A natural family of mammals including pikas and extinct forms.
Oppugnant: Tending to awaken hostility; hostile; opposing; warring.
Octoate: A salt of an octoic acid; a caprylate.
Osteology: The science which treats of the bones of the vertebrate skeleton.
&Verbar;Ornithosauria: An order of extinct flying reptiles; -- called also Pterosauria.
Overact: To act more than is necessary; to go to excess in action.
Oppressor: One who oppresses; one who imposes unjust burdens on others; one who harasses others with unjust laws or unreasonable severity.
Operatic: Of or pertaining to the opera or to operas; characteristic of, suitable for, or resembling, the opera; as, an operatic voice.
Oxheart: A large heart-shaped cherry, either black, red, or white.
one-half: one of two equal parts of a divisible whole; a half; a century and one half.
Omosternum: The anterior element of the sternum which projects forward from between the clavicles in many batrachians and is usually tipped with cartilage.
overlapping: A covering with an overlapping design, as with tiles or shingles.
Outermost: Being on the extreme external part; farthest outward; as, the outermost row.
O\u00f6phore: An alternately produced form of certain cryptogamous plants, as ferns, mosses, and the like, which bears antheridia and archegonia, and so has sexual fructification, as contrasted with the sporophore, which is nonsexual, but produces spores in countless number.  In ferns the oöphore is a minute prothallus; in mosses it is the leafy plant.
Object: Opposed; presented in opposition; also, exposed.
Overlade: To load with too great a cargo; to overburden; to overload.
Old World: The combined territories of Europe, Asia, and Africa.  The Eastern Hemisphere, as distinguished from The Americas, Australia, and the Pacific Islands.
Overmuchness: The quality or state of being in excess; superabundance.
oil-silk: Silk treated with oil to make it water-tight; -- it is used to make raincoats.
Orientality: The quality or state of being oriental or eastern.
Odyssey: An epic poem attributed to Homer, which describes the return of Ulysses to Ithaca after the siege of Troy.
Octodont: Of or pertaining to the Octodontidæ, a family of rodents which includes the coypu, and many other South American species.
Oxshoe: A shoe for oxen, consisting of a flat piece of iron nailed to the hoof.
Overinfluence: To influence in an excessive degree; to have undue influence over.
Organ: To supply with an organ or organs; to fit with organs; to organize.
one-woman: Designed for or restricted to a single person; same as one-man, but used when the person in question is female, or to avoid sexist language; as, a one-woman submarine; a one-woman show.
Ovation: A lesser kind of triumph allowed to a commander for an easy, bloodless victory, or a victory over slaves.
\u0152strual: Of or pertaining to sexual desire; -- mostly applied to brute animals; as, the œstrual period; œstrual influence.
&Verbar;O\u0153cium: One of the special zooids, or cells, of Bryozoa, destined to receive and develop ova; an ovicell. See Bryozoa.
Orphanhood: The state or condition of being an orphan; orphanage.
Olibanum: The fragrant gum resin of various species of Boswellia; Oriental frankincense.
Overflow: A flowing over, as of water or other fluid; an inundation.
ocher mutation: A mutation in which the base sequence of one of the codons in the messenger RNA has been converted to UAA.  Such a mutation may be conditionally suppressed, as can an amber mutation, by the presence of a special transfer RNA.
Osteolite: A massive impure apatite, or calcium phosphate.
Overstate: To state in too strong terms; to exaggerate.
Outnumber: To exceed in number; as, the garrison was badly outnumbered by the attacking forces.
overpass: A road or other pathway which passes over another road, railroad, or other path; as, he stopped on the street under the railroad overpass.
obesity: The state or quality of being obese; excessive body weight; incumbrance of flesh.
Ornithotomy: The anatomy or dissection of birds.
Ovariotomist: One who performs, or is skilled in, ovariotomy.
Optimate: Of or pertaining to the nobility or aristocracy.
Outweigh: To exceed in weight or value.
oddball: Eccentric; very unusual; strange; bizarre; as, an oddball request.
Oxalethyline: A poisonous nitrogenous base (C6H10N2) obtained indirectly from oxamide as a thick transparent oil which has a strong narcotic odor, and a physiological action resembling that of atropine. It is probably related to pyridine.
Octahedrite: Titanium dioxide occurring in acute octahedral crystals.
O\u00f6litic: Of or pertaining to oölite; composed of, or resembling, oölite.
Omnispective: Beholding everything; capable of seeing all things; all-seeing.
Oathable: Capable of having an oath administered to.
Overcome: To gain the superiority; to be victorious.
Oxhead: Literally, the head of an ox (emblem of cuckoldom); hence, a dolt; a blockhead.
ovulation: The formation of ova or eggs in the ovary, and the discharge of the same.  In the human female the discharge occurs about halfway between menstruation times.
Ossified: Changed to bone or something resembling bone; hardened by deposits of mineral matter of any kind; -- said of tissues.
Ort: A morsel left at a meal; a fragment; refuse; -- commonly used in the plural.
Oligo-: A combining form from Gr. 'oli`gos, few, little, small.
Osteoblast: One of the protoplasmic cells which occur in the osteogenetic layer of the periosteum, and from or around which the matrix of the bone is developed; an osteoplast.
ortho\u00ebpy: The art of uttering words correctly; a correct pronunciation of words; also, mode of pronunciation.
Outparamour: To exceed in the number of mistresses.
oligochaetous: Of or pertaining to the Oligochæta.
Orf: A bright-colored domesticated variety of the id.  See Id.
Olivil: A white crystalline substance, obtained from an exudation from the olive, and having a bitter-sweet taste and acid proporties.
Ord: An edge or point; also, a beginning.
Olivin: A complex bitter gum, found on the leaves of the olive tree; -- called also olivite.
Orb: To become round like an orb.
Ora: A money of account among the Anglo-Saxons, valued, in the Domesday Book, at twenty pence sterling.
Occult: To eclipse; to hide from sight.
Oxamidine: One of a series of bases containing the amido and the isonitroso groups united to the same carbon atom.
Outmantle: To excel in mantling; hence, to excel in splendor, as of dress.
oxidative: of or pertaining to oxidation; accompanied by oxidation.
