Organogen: A name given to any one of the four elements, carbon, hydrogen, oxygen, and nitrogen, which are especially characteristic ingredients of organic compounds; also, by extension, to other elements sometimes found in the same connection; as sulphur, phosphorus, etc.
O\u00f6stegite: One of the plates which in some Crustacea inclose a cavity wherein the eggs are hatched.
Obtuse-angled: Having an obtuse angle; as, an obtuse-angled triangle.
Occipitoaxial: Of or pertaining to the occipital bone and second vertebra, or axis.
&Verbar;Oncidium: A genus of tropical orchidaceous plants, the flower of one species of which (Oncidium Papilio) resembles a butterfly.
Obsoletism: A disused word or phrase; an archaism.
Oxlip: The great cowslip (Primula veris, var. elatior).
Osmiamic: Of, pertaining to, or designating, a nitrogenous acid of osmium, H2N2Os2O5, forming a well-known series of yellow salts.
Oilery: The business, the place of business, or the goods, of a maker of, or dealer in, oils.
oligochete: Of or pertaining to the Oligochæta.
Ortolan: A European singing bird (Emberiza hortulana), about the size of the lark, with black wings.  It is esteemed delicious food when fattened.  Called also bunting.
Octogenarian: A person eighty years, or more, of age.
Oxymel: A mixture of honey, water, vinegar, and spice, boiled to a sirup.
Ossifying: Changing into bone; becoming bone; as, the ossifying process.
\u0152coid: The colorless porous framework, or stroma, of red blood corpuscles from which the zooid, or hemoglobin and other substances of the corpuscles, may be dissolved out.
Obmutescence: A becoming dumb; loss of speech.
Ophthalmology: The science which treats of the structure, functions, and diseases of the eye.
off-and-on: discontinuous; not continuous.  Opposite of continuous.
Omnium: The aggregate value of the different stocks in which a loan to government is now usually funded.
Overlead: To domineer over; to affront; to treat with indignity.
Ovule: The rudiment of a seed.  It grows from a placenta, and consists of a soft nucleus within two delicate coatings.  The attached base of the ovule is the hilum, the coatings are united with the nucleus at the chalaza, and their minute orifice is the foramen.
Orbiculate: Made, or being, in the form of an orb; having a circular, or nearly circular, or a spheroidal, outline.
oilfish: A very large deep-water snake mackerel (Ruvettus pretiosus).
Outwrest: To extort; to draw from or forth by violence.
Overleap: To leap over or across; hence, to omit; to ignore.
Oxiodic: Pertaining to, or designating, certain compounds of iodine and oxygen.
Ombre: A large Mediterranean food fish (Umbrina cirrhosa): -- called also umbra, and umbrine.
overdramatize: to present in an overly dramatic manner.
Objurgatory: Designed to objurgate or chide; containing or expressing reproof; culpatory.
Obliquely: In an oblique manner; not directly; indirectly.
Overboard: Over the side of a ship; hence, from on board of a ship, into the water; as, to fall overboard.
Odontophore: A special structure found in the mouth of most mollusks, except bivalves.  It consists of several muscles and a cartilage which supports a chitinous radula, or lingual ribbon, armed with teeth.  Also applied to the radula alone. See Radula.
ossiculate: Of or pertaining to an ossicle.
Orthoscope: An instrument designed to show the condition of the superficial portions of the eye.
operant conditioning: A process for causing animals to behave in a specific manner by rewarding or punishing the animal each time it performs a certain act; after a time, the animal comes to associate the reward or punishment with the act, and will increase or decrease the frequency of performing that act.
Okapia: A genus of mammals comprising the okapis.
Objectivity: The state, quality, or relation of being objective; character of the object or of the objective.
Oviform: Having the form or figure of an egg; egg-shaped; as, an oviform leaf.
&Verbar;Osteomalacia: A disease of the bones, in which they lose their earthy material, and become soft, flexible, and distorted.  Also called malacia.
Organule: One of the essential cells or elements of an organ. See Sense organule, under Sense.
Over-arm: Done (as bowling or pitching) with the arm raised above the shoulder. See Overhard.
Ordinative: Tending to ordain; directing; giving order.
Oriskany: Designating, or pertaining to, certain beds, chiefly limestone, characteristic of the latest period of the Silurian age.
Outfoot: To outrun or outwalk; hence, of a vessel, to outsail.
Opportunity: Fit or convenient time or situation; a time or place permitting or favorable for the execution of a purpose; a suitable combination of conditions; suitable occasion; chance.
Obturation: The act of stopping up, or closing, an opening.
Oceanology: That branch of science which relates to the ocean.
osmogene: An apparatus, consisting of a number of cells whose sides are of parchment paper, for conducting the process of osmosis.  It is used especially in sugar refining to remove potassium salts from the molasses.
Omani: A native or inhabitant of Oman.
&Verbar;osteoclasis: The operation of breaking a bone in order to correct deformity.
&Verbar;Onappo: A nocturnal South American monkey (Callithrix discolor), noted for its agility; -- called also ventriloquist monkey.
Oxidize: To combine with oxygen, or subject to the action of oxygen, or of an oxidizing agent.
Orchestration: The arrangement of music for an orchestra; orchestral treatment of a composition; -- called also instrumentation.
Overinform: To inform, fill, or animate, excessively.
Outscorn: To confront, or subdue, with greater scorn.
Overtempt: To tempt exceedingly, or beyond the power of resistance.
Ophicleide: A large brass wind instrument, formerly used in the orchestra and in military bands, having a loud tone, deep pitch, and a compass of three octaves; -- now generally supplanted by bass and contrabass tubas.  It developed from the older wooden instrument called the serpent.
Outdoor: Being, or done, in the open air; being or done outside of certain buildings, as poorhouses, hospitals, etc.; as, outdoor exercise; outdoor relief; outdoor patients.
Ovate-acuminate: Having an ovate form, but narrowed at the end into a slender point.
Officious: Pertaining to, or being in accordance with, duty.
O\u00f6phytic: Of or pertaining to an oöphyte.
&Verbar;Oreades: A group of butterflies which includes the satyrs. See Satyr, 2.
Orthopraxy: The treatment of deformities in the human body by mechanical appliances.
One: To cause to become one; to gather into a single whole; to unite; to assimilite.
object-oriented: Using data structures called objects, which encapsulate data and typically are accessed by passing messages, which in turn may trigger internal procedures within the object which are invisible outside the object.
Orvietan: A kind of antidote for poisons; a counter poison formerly in vogue.
okapi: A peculiar mammal (Okapia johnstoni) closely related to the giraffe, discovered in the deep forests of Belgian Congo in 1900.  It is smaller than an ox, and somewhat like a giraffe, except that the neck is much shorter.  Like the giraffe, it has no dewclaws.  There is a small prominence on each frontal bone of the male.  The color of the body is chiefly reddish chestnut, the cheeks are yellowish white, and the fore and hind legs above the knees and the haunches are striped with purplish black and cream color.
Oscinine: Of or pertaining to the Oscines.
Obiism: Belief in, or the practice of, the obi superstitions and rites.
Observational: Of or pertaining to observation; consisting of, or containing, observations.
Omphalode: The central part of the hilum of a seed, through which the nutrient vessels pass into the rhaphe or the chalaza; -- called also omphalodium.
Old-fashioned: Formed according to old or obsolete fashion or pattern; belonging to or characteristic of times past; adhering to old customs, styles, or ideas; as, an old-fashioned dress, girl; old-fashioned wire-rimmed glasses.
Orpheus: The famous mythic Thracian poet, son of the Muse Calliope, and husband of Eurydice.  He is reputed to have had power to entrance beasts and inanimate objects by the music of his lyre.
Oriental: A native or inhabitant of the Orient or some Eastern part of the world; an Asiatic.
Outer: One who puts out, ousts, or expels; also, an ouster; dispossession.
Ovate-oblong: Oblong, with one end narrower than the other; ovato-oblong.
off-licence: a store that sells alcoholic beverages for consumption elsewhere.
Optime: One of those who stand in the second rank of honors, immediately after the wranglers, in the University of Cambridge, England.  They are divided into senior and junior optimes.
Outbreast: To surpass in singing. See Breast, n., 6.
Ottrelite: A micaceous mineral occurring in small scales.  It is characteristic of certain crystalline schists.
Outmost: Farthest from the middle or interior; farthest outward; outermost.
ostracoderm: Any of several extinct fishlike jawless vertebrates having a heavily armored body; of the Paleozoic.
Open verdict: A verdict on a preliminary investigation, finding the fact of a crime but not stating the criminal, or finding the fact of a violent death without disclosing the cause.
orange: Of or pertaining to an orange; of the color of an orange; reddish yellow; as, an orange ribbon.
Oary: Having the form or the use of an oar; as, the swan's oary feet.
&Verbar;\u0152il-de-b\u0153uf: A circular or oval window; -- generally used of architecture of the 17th and 18th centuries.  A famous room in the palace of Versailles bears this name, from the oval window opening into it.
Overlap: The lapping of one thing over another; as, an overlap of six inches; an overlap of a slate on a roof.
&Verbar;Orabassu: A South American monkey of the genus Callithrix, esp. Callithrix Moloch.
\u0152: a diphthong, employed in the Latin language, and thence in the English language, as the representative of the Greek diphthong oi.  In many words in common use, e alone stands instead of œ.  Classicists prefer to write the diphthong oe separate in Latin words.
outside-group: Of or pertaining to marriage outside a class or tribe, in cultures where that is required by custom or law.
Operculate: Closed by a lid or cover, as the capsules of the mosses.
Ovipositor: The organ with which many insects and some other animals deposit their eggs.  Some ichneumon files have a long ovipositor fitted to pierce the eggs or larvæ of other insects, in order to lay their own eggs within the same.
off-center: situated away from the center or axis.
Octostichous: In eight vertical ranks, as leaves on a stem.
Olla: A pot or jar having a wide mouth; a cinerary urn, especially one of baked clay.
Omphalomesenteric: Of or pertaining to the umbilicus and mesentery; omphalomesaraic; as, the omphalomesenteric arteries and veins of a fetus.
Ornithomancy: Divination by means of birds, their flight, etc.
O\u00f6phyte: Any plant of a proposed class or grand division (collectively termed oöphytes or Oöphyta), which have their sexual reproduction accomplished by motile antherozoids acting on oöspheres, either while included in their oögonia or after exclusion.
&Verbar;Orthis: An extinct genus of Brachiopoda, abundant in the Paleozoic rocks.
\u0152nanthylous: Of, pertaining to, or designating, an acid formerly supposed to be the acid of œnanthylic ether, but now known to be a mixture of higher acids, especially capric acid.
Oryx: A genus of African antelopes which includes the gemsbok, the leucoryx, the bisa antelope (Oryx beisa), and the beatrix antelope (Oryx beatrix) of Arabia.
Open-mouthed: Having the mouth open; gaping; hence, greedy; clamorous.
Overspeak: To exceed in speaking; to speak too much; to use too many words.
Oxyquinoline: Hydroxy quinoline; a phenol derivative of quinoline, -- called also carbostyril.
Overlive: To live too long, too luxuriously, or too actively.
Occasionable: Capable of being occasioned or caused.
Outluster: To excel in brightness or luster.
Oily: Consisting of oil; containing oil; having the nature or qualities of oil; unctuous; oleaginous; as, oily matter or substance.
Opponent: One who opposes; an adversary; an antagonist; a foe.
Okenite: A massive and fibrous mineral of a whitish color, chiefly hydrous silicate of lime.
&Verbar;Octogynia: A Linnaean order of plants having eight pistils.
Octosyllabic: Consisting of or containing eight syllables.
Oversell: To sell for a higher price than; to exceed in selling price.
obsess: To be excessively or persistently preoccupied with something; -- usually used with on or over; as, to obsess over an imagined insult.
Overreacher: One who overreaches; one who cheats; a cheat.
Oleaceae: A natural family of trees and shrubs having berries or drupes or capsules as fruits; the olive family; sometimes placed in the order Oleales; it includes the olive; ash; jasmine; privet; and lilac.
Outrageous: Of the nature of an outrage; exceeding the limits of right, reason, or decency; such as to cause outrage; involving or doing an outrage; furious; violent; atrocious.
Obscurant: One who obscures; one who prevents enlightenment or hinders the progress of knowledge and wisdom.
Orismology: That department of natural history which treats of technical terms; the science of defining technical terms.
Outlook: The act of looking out; watch.
old-world: Characteristic of former times especially in Europe; as, an old-world cottage.
&Verbar;Osteoperiostitis: Inflammation of a bone and its periosteum.
Octant: The eighth part of a circle; an arc of 45 degrees.
Orcein: A reddish brown amorphous dyestuff, C7H7NO3, obtained from orcin, and forming the essential coloring matter of cudbear and archil.  It is closely related to litmus.
Oblatrate: To bark or snarl, as a dog.
Occamy: An alloy imitating gold or silver.
obscurity: The quality or state of being obscure.
&Verbar;O\u00f6: A beautiful bird (Moho nobilis) of the Hawaiian Islands.  It yields the brilliant yellow feathers formerly used in making the royal robes.  Called also yellow-tufted honeysucker.
owned: having an owner; often used in combination; as, state-owned railways.  Opposite of unowned.
-ous: An adjective suffix meaning full of, abounding in, having, possessing the qualities of, like; as in gracious, abounding in grace; arduous, full of ardor; bulbous, having bulbs, bulblike; riotous, poisonous, piteous, joyous, etc.
Occasionally: In an occasional manner; on occasion; at times, as convenience requires or opportunity offers; not regularly.
&Verbar;Oculina: A genus of tropical corals, usually branched, and having a very volid texture.
Overgive: To give over; to surrender; to yield.
&Verbar;Ophiomorpha: An order of tailless amphibians having a slender, wormlike body with regular annulations, and usually with minute scales imbedded in the skin.  The limbs are rudimentary or lacking.  It includes the cæcilians.  Called also Gymnophiona and Ophidobatrachia.
overlearn: To learn (a fact or skill) repetitively, beyond the point where it can be immediately recalled; in experimental psychology, to continue to learn beyond the point where the criterion of adequate learning has been reached.
Offhand: Instant; unprepared; ready; extemporaneous; unrehearsed; as, an offhand speech; offhand excuses; an offhand comment.
Odor: Any smell, whether fragrant or offensive; scent; perfume.
Orangite: An orange-yellow variety of the mineral thorite, found in Norway.
Outmaneuver: To surpass, or get an advantage of, in maneuvering; to outwit or frustrate by clever stratagems; to outgeneral.
Outfit: A fitting out, or equipment, as of a ship for a voyage, or of a person for an expedition in an unoccupied region or residence in a foreign land; the expense of, or allowance made for, equipment, as by the government of the United States to a diplomatic agent going abroad.
Overreach: The act of striking the heel of the fore foot with the toe of the hind foot; -- said of horses.
Obeisant: Ready to obey; reverent; deferential; also, servilely submissive.
Obliqueness: Quality or state of being oblique.
Oxyacid: An acid containing oxygen, as chloric acid or sulphuric acid; -- contrasted with the hydracids, which contain no oxygen, as hydrochloric acid. See Acid, and Hydroxy-.
Originate: To take first existence; to have origin or beginning; to begin to exist or act; as, the scheme originated with the governor and council.
Obfuscate: To darken; to obscure; to becloud.
Oneliness: The state of being one or single.
Obstetrician: One skilled in obstetrics; an accoucheur; especially, a physician who specializes in obstetrics.
Overfullness: The state of being excessively or abnormally full, so as to cause overflow, distention, or congestion; excess of fullness; surfeit.
overdress: To dress or adorn to excess; to dress too much; to dress too formally for an informal occasion.
Occiput: The back, or posterior, part of the head or skull; the region of the occipital bone.
Outstanding: That stands out; undischarged; uncollected; not paid; as, outstanding obligations.
Outshine: To surpass in splendor, excellence, or achievement.
orchestrated: Arranged for performance by an orchestra; -- of a musical composition.
out-tray: a wood or metal receptacle placed on a desk to hold documents which have been processed, prior to transfer to a different person.
Oval: A body or figure in the shape of an egg, or popularly, of an ellipse.
Overabound: To be exceedingly plenty or superabundant.
-ock: A suffix used to form diminutives; as, bullock, hillock.
Outbalance: To outweight; to exceed in weight or effect.
obechi: A large Western African tree (Triplochiton scleroxcylon) having large palmately lobed leaves and axillary cymose panicles of small white flowers and one-winged seeds; it yields soft white to pale yellow wood.
&Verbar;Odontocete: A subdivision of Cetacea, including the sperm whale, dolphins, etc.; the toothed whales.
&Verbar;Os: A mouth; an opening; an entrance.
&Verbar;Om: A mystic syllable or ejaculation used by Hindus and Buddhists in religious rites, -- orig. among the Hindus an exclamation of assent, like Amen, then an invocation, and later a symbol of the trinity formed by Vishnu, Siva, and Brahma.
Omnicorporeal: Comprehending or including all bodies; embracing all substance.
Outkeeper: An attachment to a surveyor's compass for keeping tally in chaining.
Oil: To smear or rub over with oil; to lubricate with oil; to anoint with oil.
Oleraceous: Pertaining to pot herbs; of the nature or having the qualities of herbs for cookery; esculent.
off-peak: Having less than maximal use or demand or activity; -- of a period of time occurring as a defined part of a time cycle; as, off-peak telepone rates are available at night and on weekends; off-peak fares.
Outpass: To pass beyond; to exceed in progress.
\u0152strian: Of or pertaining to the gadflies.
Ottawas: A tribe of Indians who, when first known, lived on the Ottawa River.  Most of them subsequently migrated to the southwestern shore of Lake Superior.
&Verbar;O\u00f6theca: An egg case, especially those of many kinds of mollusks, and of some insects, as the cockroach.  Cf. Oœcium.
\u0152nanthic: Having, or imparting, the odor characteristic of the bouquet of wine; specifically used, formerly, to designate an acid (oenanthic acid) whose ethereal salts were supposed to occasion the peculiar bouquet, or aroma, of old wine.  Cf. Œnanthylic.
Octyl: A hypothetical hydrocarbon radical regarded as an essential residue of octane, and as entering into its derivatives; as, octyl alcohol.
outpour: A flowing out; a free discharge.
Osmious: Denoting those compounds of osmium in which the element has a valence relatively lower than in the osmic compounds; as, osmious chloride.
Ounce: A feline quadruped (Felis irbis syn. Felis uncia) resembling the leopard in size, and somewhat in color, but it has longer and thicker fur, which forms a short mane on the back.  The ounce is pale yellowish gray, with irregular dark spots on the neck and limbs, and dark rings on the body.  It inhabits the lofty mountain ranges of Asia. Called also once.
Osteopathist: One who practices osteopathy; an osteopath.
ostracod: A member of the Ostracoda, an order of tiny marine and freshwater crustaceans with a shrimplike body enclosed in a bivalve shell.
Opercle: Any one of the bony plates which support the gill covers of fishes; an opercular bone.
Overpersuade: To persuade or influence against one's inclination or judgment.
Observer: One who observes, or pays attention to, anything; especially, one engaged in, or trained to habits of, close and exact observation; as, an astronomical observer.
&Verbar;Oleamen: A soft ointment prepared from oil.
Oleaster: The wild olive tree (Olea Europea, var. sylvestris).
off-season: of or relating to a season of less than maximum demand; as, off-season hotel rates are lower.
Overdare: To dare too much or rashly; to be too daring.
Owler: One who owls; esp., one who conveys contraband goods. See Owling, n.
Odmyl: A volatile liquid obtained by boiling sulphur with linseed oil.  It has an unpleasant garlic odor.
Overking: A king who has sovereignty over inferior kings or ruling princes.
Oleaceous: Of, pertaining to, or resembling, a natural family of plants (Oleaceæ), mostly trees and shrubs, of which the olive is the type.  It includes also the ash, the lilac, the true jasmine, and fringe tree.
Outdream: To pass, or escape, while dreaming.
Overseer: One who oversees; a superintendent; a supervisor; as, an overseer of a mill; specifically, one or certain public officers; as, an overseer of the poor; an overseer of highways.
Obstinate: Pertinaciously adhering to an opinion, purpose, or course; persistent; not yielding to reason, arguments, or other means; stubborn; pertinacious; -- usually implying unreasonableness.
Outrun: To exceed, or leave behind, in running; to run faster than; to outstrip; to go beyond.
Obtund: To reduce the edge, pungency, or violent action of; to dull; to blunt; to deaden; to quell; as, to obtund the acrimony of the gall.
Ocular: The eyepiece of an optical instrument, as of a telescope or microscope.
Oblanceolate: Lanceolate in the reversed order, that is, narrowing toward the point of attachment more than toward the apex.
Ordinaryship: The state of being an ordinary.
Overground: Situated over or above ground; as, the overground portion of a plant.
operational: of or pertaining to operations; as, operational procedure.
-or: A noun suffix denoting an act; a state or quality; as in error, fervor, pallor, candor, etc.
Otherwhere: In or to some other place, or places; elsewhere.
Osculation: The act of kissing; a kiss.
Obsoleteness: The state of being obsolete, or no longer used; a state of desuetude.
Octamerous: Having the parts in eights; as, an octamerous flower; octamerous mesenteries in polyps.
off-the-cuff: with little or no preparation or forethought; unrehearsed; extemporaneous; offhand.
Oblateness: The quality or state of being oblate.
Obstreperous: Attended by, or making, a loud and tumultuous noise; clamorous; noisy; vociferous.
Omphalic: Of or pertaining to the umbilicus, or navel.
Occision: A killing; the act of killing.
Obscurement: The act of obscuring, or the state of being obscured; obscuration.
Ovism: The old theory that the egg contains the whole embryo of the future organism and the germs of all subsequent offsprings and is merely awakened to activity by the spermatozoön; -- opposed to spermism or animalculism.
&Verbar;Odontopteryx: An extinct Eocene bird having the jaws strongly serrated, or dentated, but destitute of true teeth. It was found near London.
Once: For one time; by limitation to the number one; not twice nor any number of times more than one.
Orthocarbonic: Designating a complex ether, C.(OC2H5)4, which is obtained as a liquid of a pleasant ethereal odor by means of chlorpicrin, and is believed to be a derivative of the hypothetical normal carbonic acid, C.(OH)4.
Oligomerous: Having few members in each set of organs; as, an oligomerous flower.
Ominous: Of or pertaining to an omen or to omens; being or exhibiting an omen; significant; portentous; -- formerly used both in a favorable and unfavorable sense; now chiefly in the latter; foreboding or foreshowing evil; inauspicious; as, an ominous dread.
Overharden: To harden too much; to make too hard.
&Verbar;Oceanus: The god of the great outer sea, or the river which was believed to flow around the whole earth.
oenanthate: A salt or ester of oenanthic acid; as, testosterone oenanthate is sold as an anabolic steroid; also called enanthate.
&Verbar;Osmaterium: One of a pair of scent organs which the larvæ of certain butterflies emit from the first body segment, either above or below.
Orthodoxness: The quality or state of being orthodox; orthodoxy.
Overeye: To superintend; to oversee; to inspect.
Open sea: A sea open to all nations. See Mare clausum.
outfielder: A person who plays in the outfield.
obliterating: making undecipherable or imperceptible; as, obliterating mists.
Obtestation: The act of obtesting; supplication; protestation.
Olivenite: An olive-green mineral, a hydrous arseniate of copper (Cu2(AsO4)(OH)); olive ore.
&Verbar;\u0152il-de-perdrix: Characterized by, or decorated with, small round points, spots, or rings; as, œil-de-perdrix pattern.
Ouarine: A Brazilian monkey of the genus Mycetes.
Outprize: To prize beyong value, or in excess; to exceed in value.
Orbed: Having the form of an orb; round.
Orbiculation: The state or quality of being orbiculate; orbicularness.
Occursion: A meeting; a clash; a collision.
Ophthalmia: An inflammation of the membranes or coats of the eye or of the eyeball.
Ophthalmic: Of, pertaining to, or in the region of, the eye; ocular; as the ophthalmic, or orbitonasal, nerve, a division of the trigeminal, which gives branches to the lachrymal gland, eyelids, nose, and forehead.
Overgrassed: Overstocked, or overgrown, or covered, with grass.
Outsell: To exceed in amount of sales; to sell more than.
Outdated: Being out of date; antiquated; outmoded; unfashionable.
one-hand: Employing one hand; as, the one-hand alphabet. See Dactylology.
Optometer: An instrument for measuring the distance of distinct vision, mainly for the selection of eveglasses.
Ouster: A putting out of possession; dispossession; disseizin; -- of a person.
Omnivorous: All-devouring; eating everything indiscriminately; as, omnivorous vanity; an omnivorous intellect.
Opinionable: Being, or capable of being, a matter of opinion; that can be thought; not positively settled; as, an opinionable doctrine.
Orthograph: An orthographic projection, sometimes partly in section, esp. of a building.
Obduce: To draw over, as a covering.
Olitory: Of or pertaining to, or produced in, a kitchen garden; used for kitchen purposes; as, olitory seeds.
Overtone: One of the harmonics faintly heard with and at a higher frequency than a fundamental tone as it dies away, produced by some aliquot portion of the vibrating sting or column of air which yields the fundamental tone; one of the natural harmonic scale of tones, as the octave, twelfth, fifteenth, etc.; an aliquot or “partial” tone; a harmonic. See Harmonic, and Tone.
&Verbar;\u0152dema: A swelling from effusion of watery fluid in the cellular tissue beneath the skin or mucous membrance; dropsy of the subcutaneous cellular tissue.
Oomiac: A long, broad boat used by the Eskimos.
Oast: A kiln to dry hops or malt; a cockle.
Osteologist: One who is skilled in osteology; an osteologer.
Osmic: Pertaining to, derived from, or containing, osmium; specifically, designating those compounds in which it has a valence higher than in other lower compounds; as, osmic oxide.
overcoat: A coat worn over the other clothing; a greatcoat; a topcoat.
off-roader: a bicycle with a sturdy frame and fat tires; originally designed for riding in mountainous country;  amountain bike.
Outstand: To resist effectually; to withstand; to sustain without yielding.
Outhaul: A rope used for hauling out a sail upon a spar; -- opposite of inhaul.
Overpaint: To color or describe too strongly.
Officially: By the proper officer; by virtue of the proper authority; in pursuance of the special powers vested in an officer or office; as, accounts or reports officially verified or rendered; letters officially communicated; persons officially notified.
Obsignation: The act of sealing or ratifying; the state of being sealed or confirmed; confirmation, as by the Holy Spirit.
outfangthef: A thief from without or abroad, taken within a lord's fee or liberty.
&Verbar;Oreosoma: A genus of small oceanic fishes, remarkable for the large conical tubercles which cover the under surface.
&Verbar;Orthopoda: An extinct order of reptiles which stood erect on the hind legs, and resembled birds in the structure of the feet, pelvis, and other parts.
Orifice: A mouth or aperture, as of a tube, pipe, etc.; an opening; as, the orifice of an artery or vein; the orifice of a wound.
off-Broadway: A group of low-budget theaters located outside the Broadway area in Manhattan.
Outrede: To surpass in giving rede, or counsel.
Odalman: A man or woman having odal, or able to share in it by inheritance.
ovoflavin: An uncommon name for riboflavin, also called vitamin B2.
Ovate-rotundate: Having a form intermediate between that of an egg and a sphere; roundly ovate.
Outdo: To go beyond in performance; to excel; to surpass.
Outdare: To surpass in daring; to overcome by courage; to brave.
Outwear: To wear out; to consume or destroy by wearing.
Orris: A sort of gold or silver lace.
Outbrazen: To bear down with a brazen face; to surpass in impudence.
Ocelot: An American feline carnivore (Felis pardalis).  It ranges from the Southwestern United States to Patagonia.  It is covered with blackish ocellated spots and blotches, which are variously arranged.  The ground color varies from reddish gray to tawny yellow.
Oread: One of the nymphs of mountains and grottoes.
Ostrogoth: One of the Eastern Goths. See Goth.
Oxanilamide: A white crystalline nitrogenous substance, obtained indirectly by the action of cyanogen on aniline, and regarded as an anilide of oxamic acid; -- called also phenyl oxamide.
Openwork: Anything so constructed or manufactured (in needlework, carpentry, metal work, etc.) as to show openings through its substance; work that is perforated or pierced.
Opsonation: A catering; a buying of provisions.
outtake: A portion of a recorded performance which is eliminated in the editing process and is not included in the final commercial presentation.  The recording may be audio or visual or both, but is usually of a film or television performance.  Outtakes often include mistakes or lower quality performances, and sometimes blunders.  The latter type are occasionally presented separately to the public for amusement.
Overhang: In a general sense, that which just out or projects; a projection; also, the measure of the projection; as, the overhang is five feet.
obituary: That which pertains to, or is called forth by, the obit or death of a person; esp., an account of a deceased person.
Oneself: A reflexive form of the indefinite pronoun one.  Commonly written as two words, one's self.
Offering: The act of an offerer; a proffering.
Offing: That part of the sea at a good distance from the shore, or where there is deep water and no need of a pilot; also, distance from the shore; as, the ship had ten miles offing; we saw a ship in the offing.
Orgeat: A sirup in which, formerly, a decoction of barley entered, but which is now prepared with an emulsion of almonds, -- used to flavor beverages or edibles.
Oxford: Of or pertaining to the city or university of Oxford, England.
outbreak: A bursting forth; eruption; insurrection; mutiny; revolt.
Otopathy: A diseased condition of the ear.
Orthoclastic: Breaking in directions at right angles to each other; -- said of the monoclinic feldspars.
Orbital: Of or pertaining to an orbit.
Oppugn: To fight against; to attack; to be in conflict with; to oppose; to resist.
Oxyntic: Acid; producing acid; -- applied especially to certain glands and cells in the stomach.
Ophidian: Of or pertaining to the Ophidia; belonging to serpents.
overfamiliar: Taking undue liberties; assuming an unwarranted tone of familiarity.
oligochaete: Any of an order of hermaphroditic terrestrial and aquatic annelids (including the earthworms) having bristles borne singly along the length of the body; a member of the Oligochaeta.
overcast: Completely or almost completely covered over with clouds; -- of the sky.
Oxhide: The skin of an ox, or leather made from it.
Oligarchic: Of or pertaining to oligarchy, or government by a few.
Oxanilic: Pertaining to, or derived from, oxalic acid and aniline; -- used to designate an acid obtained in white crystalline scales by heating these substances together.
Ogeechee lime: The acid, olive-shaped, drupaceous fruit of a species of tupelo (Nyssa capitata) which grows in swamps in Georgia and Florida.
outrigger: Any spar or projecting timber run out for temporary use, as from a ship's mast, to hold a rope or a sail extended, or from a building, to support hoisting teckle.
one-eared: Relating to or having or hearing with only one ear; monaural.  Opposite of binaural.
Onocerin: A white crystalline waxy substance extracted from the root of the leguminous plant Ononis spinosa.
Ordinalism: The state or quality of being ordinal.
outrigged: rigged with a structure projecting from or over the side of a boat for various purposes; having an outrigger; -- to prevent capsizing or to support an oarlock or to help secure a mast etc.  See outrigger
Oxalantin: A white crystalline nitrogenous substance (C6H4N4O5)  obtained by the reduction of parabanic acid; -- called also leucoturic acid.
Outburst: A bursting forth; as, an outburst of laughter.
Odonto-: A combining form from Gr. 'odoy`s, 'odo`ntos, a tooth.
odd-pinnate: Pinnate with a single leaflet at the apex; -- of a leaf shape.
off-limits: barred to a designated group; as, the topless bar is off-lints to military personnel.
Oleic: Pertaining to, derived from, or contained in, oil; as, oleic acid, an acid of the acrylic acid series found combined with glyceryl in the form of olein in certain animal and vegetable fats and oils, such as sperm oil, olive oil, etc.  At low temperatures the acid is crystalline, but melts to an oily liquid above 14° C.
Olein: A fat, liquid at ordinary temperatures, but solidifying at temperatures below 0° C., found abundantly in both the animal and vegetable kingdoms (see Palmitin).  It dissolves solid fats, especially at 30-40° C.  Chemically, olein is a glyceride of oleic acid; and, as three molecules of the acid are united to one molecule of glycerol to form the fat, it is technically known as triolein.  It is also called elain.
Ondograph: An instrument for autographically recording the wave forms of varying currents, esp. rapidly varying alternating currents.
Omni-: A combining form denoting all, every, everywhere; as in omnipotent, all-powerful; omnipresent; omnivorous.
Overfly: To cross or pass over by flight.
Officer: To furnish with officers; to appoint officers over.
Offend: To transgress the moral or divine law; to commit a crime; to stumble; to sin.
Obediently: In an obedient manner; with obedience.
Odontolite: A fossil tooth colored a bright blue by phosphate of iron. It is used as an imitation of turquoise, and hence called bone turquoise.
Ouphe: A fairy; a goblin; an elf.
Ohm: The standard unit in the measure of electrical resistance, being the resistance of a circuit in which a potential difference of one volt produces a current of one ampére.  As defined by the International Electrical Congress in 1893, and by United States Statute, it is a resistance substantially equal to 109 units of resistance of the C. G. S. system of electro-magnetic units, and is represented by the resistance offered to an unvarying electric current by a column of mercury at the temperature of melting ice 14.4521 grams in mass, of a constant cross-sectional area, and of the length of 106.3 centimeters. As thus defined it is called the international ohm.
Opinator: One fond of his own opinions; one who holds an opinion.
Overthwartly: In an overthwart manner; across; also, perversely.
Ovenbird: Any species of the genus Furnarius, allied to the creepers.  They inhabit South America and the West Indies, and construct curious oven-shaped nests.
Obtrusive: Disposed to obtrude; inclined to intrude or thrust one's self or one's opinions upon others, or to enter uninvited; forward; pushing; intrusive.
Obduration: A hardening of the heart; hardness of heart.
Otheoscope: An instrument for exhibiting the repulsive action produced by light or heat in an exhausted vessel; a modification of the radiometer.
Opisthography: A writing upon the back of anything, as upon the back of a leaf or sheet already written upon on one side.
Obligate: To bring or place under obligation, moral or legal; to hold by a constraining motive.
Onomastic: Applied to a signature when the body of the instrument is in another's handwriting.
Oscillancy: The state of oscillating; a seesaw kind of motion.
Overpraising: The act of praising unduly; excessive praise.
Oceanic: Of or pertaining to the ocean; found or formed in or about, or produced by, the ocean; frequenting the ocean, especially mid-ocean.
Oceania: A large group of islands in the south Pacific sometimes including Australasia and the Malay Archipelago.
Opalesce: To give forth a play of colors, like the opal.
Orlop: The lowest deck of a vessel, esp. of a ship of war, consisting of a platform laid over the beams in the hold, on which the cables are coiled.
Overfrieze: To cover with a frieze, or as with a frieze.
Overawful: Awful, or reverential, in an excessive degree.
ostracism: Banishment by popular vote, -- a means adopted at Athens to rid the city of a person whose talent and influence gave umbrage.
Over: A certain number of balls (usually four) delivered successively from behind one wicket, after which the ball is bowled from behind the other wicket as many times, the fielders changing places.
Optogram: An image of external objects fixed on the retina by the photochemical action of light on the visual purple. See Optography.
Overwasted: Wasted or worn out; consumed; spent
Oppletion: The act of filling up, or the state of being filled up; fullness.
one-eyed: having or showing only one eye; as, one-eyed Jacks are wild; the three one-eyed Cyclopes of Greek myth.
Ordinable: Capable of being ordained or appointed.
octet: A composition for eight parts, usually for eight solo instruments or voices.
Oxanilide: A white crystalline substance, resembling oxanilamide, obtained by heating aniline oxalate, and regarded as a double anilide of oxalic acid; -- called also diphenyl oxamide.
outlandishness: The quality of being strikingly out of the ordinary; the quality of being outlandish{2}.
Orthognathous: Having the front of the head, or the skull, nearly perpendicular, not retreating backwards above the jaws; -- opposed to prognathous. See Gnathic index, under Gnathic.
Orderless: Being without order or regularity; disorderly; out of rule.
Official: One who holds an office; esp., a subordinate executive officer or attendant.
oiled: Covered or treated with oil; dressed with, or soaked in, oil.
Overthwartness: The state of being overthwart; perverseness.
Oppositipetalous: Placed in front of a petal.
Obstriction: The state of being constrained, bound, or obliged; that which constrains or obliges; obligation; bond.
Ovology: That branch of natural history which treats of the origin and functions of eggs.
&Verbar;Ophiuchus: A constellation in the Northern Hemisphere, delineated as a man holding a serpent in his hands; -- called also Serpentarius.
Oxycrate: A Mixture of water and vinegar.
Ogre: An imaginary monster, or hideous giant of fairy tales, who lived on human beings; hence, any frightful giant; a cruel monster.
organelle: a specialized part of a cell performing a specific function, usually visible under the microscope as a distinct object; it is analogous to an organ{2}, but on a microscopic scale.
one-dimensional: having only one dimension; as, a line is a one-dimensional object; a one-dimensional array.
Ornithotomist: One who is skilled in ornithotomy.
obliterated: destroyed so thoroughly as to be unrecognizable or imperceptible.
Obelize: To designate with an obelus; to mark as doubtful or spirituous.
Osteogen: The soft tissue, or substance, which, in developing bone, ultimately undergoes ossification.
Overstep: To step over or beyond; to transgress; as, to overstep the bounds of propriety.
Opener: One who, or that which, opens.
Orang-outang: An arboreal anthropoid ape (Pongo pygmaeus, formerly Simia satyrus), which inhabits Borneo and Sumatra.  Often called simply orang.  It is now an endangered species.
Obscuration: The act or operation of obscuring; the state of being obscured; as, the obscuration of the moon in an eclipse.
osmograph: An instrument for recording the height of the liquid in an endosmometer or for registering osmotic pressures.
Ovine: Of or pertaining to sheep; consisting of sheep.
&Verbar;Octocerata: A suborder of Cephalopoda including Octopus, Argonauta, and allied genera, having eight arms around the head; -- called also Octopoda.
Omahas: A tribe of Indians who inhabited the south side of the Missouri River.  They are now partly civilized and occupy a reservation in Nebraska.
Old Dominion: Virginia; -- a name of uncertain origin, perh. from the old designation of the colony as “the Colony and Dominion of Virginia.”
O\u00f6logy: The science of eggs in relation to their coloring, size, shape, and number.
ovenware: Heat-resistant dishware in which food can be cooked as well as served.
oil spill: A layer of oil floating on water or covering the shoreline of a body of water; -- usually petroleum which has leaked from an oil tanker.
&Verbar;Opisthotonos: A tetanic spasm in which the body is bent backwards and stiffened.
Operculigenous: Producing an operculum; -- said of the foot, or part of the foot, of certain mollusks.
Overlash: To drive on rashly; to go to excess; hence, to exaggerate; to boast.
Outcome: That which comes out of, or follows from, something else; issue; result; consequence; upshot.
Ohmmeter: An instrument for indicating directly the electrical resistance of a circuit in ohms.
Oblationer: One who makes an offering as an act worship or reverence.
\u0152nothionic: Pertaining to an acid now called sulphovinic acid or ethyl sulphuric acid.
&Verbar;Ottava rima: A stanza of eight lines of heroic verse, with three rhymes, the first six lines rhyming alternately and the last two forming a couplet.  It was used by Byron in “Don Juan,” by Keats in “Isabella,” by Shelley in “The Witch of Atlas,” etc.
Osmanli: A Turkish official; one of the dominant tribe of Turks; loosely, any Turk.
Offense: The act of offending in any sense; esp., a crime or a sin, an affront or an injury.
Orbitary: Situated around the orbit; as, the orbitary feathers of a bird.
Octopetalous: Having eight petals or flower leaves.
Oculomotor: Of or pertaining to the movement of the eye; -- applied especially to the common motor nerves (or third pair of cranial nerves) which supply many of the muscles of the orbit.
Overswell: To swell or rise above; to overflow.
Offlet: A pipe to let off water.
Overscrupulousness: The quality or state of being overscrupulous; excess of scrupulousness.
Offertory: The act of offering, or the thing offered.
\u0152nology: Knowledge of wine, scientific or practical.
osmotic pressure: The pressure which a solution of a substance in a liquid exerts on a semipermeable membrane, through which the solvent can diffuse but the dissolved substance (the solute) cannot diffuse, when separated across the membrane from the pure solvent.  In general, the osmotic pressure will depend almost proportionally up to certain concentrations upon the molal concentration of the solute.
&Verbar;Opisthobranchia: A division of gastropod Mollusca, in which the breathing organs are usually situated behind the heart.  It includes the tectibranchs and nudibranchs.
Oxidation: The act or process of oxidizing, or the state or result of being oxidized.
Orchestral: Of or pertaining to an orchestra; suitable for, or performed in or by, an orchestra.
Ormosia: A genus of tropical shrubs and trees having usually odd-pinnate leaves with large leaflets and pink to reddish wood.
Octic: Of the eighth degree or order.
Overfreight: To put too much freight in or upon; to load too full, or too heavily; to overload.
Orkneyan: Of or pertaining to the Orkney islands.
old-womanish: Like an old woman; anile; primly fastidious; old-maidish.
Opercular: The principal opercular bone or operculum of fishes.
Octoroon: The offspring of a quadroon and a white person; a mestee.
Omohyoid: Of or pertaining to the shoulder and the hyoid bone; as, the omohyoid muscle.
Ophiophagous: Feeding on serpents; -- said of certain birds and reptiles.
Omphalotomy: The operation of dividing the navel-string.
